<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Belgium-Subway     03-11 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Belgium-Subway,0130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subway Crime Increased 26-Fold During 1980s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petty crime in the Brussels subway has
increased 26-fold in the 1980s, but the Metro remains among the
safest subway systems in the world, transit authorities say.
   Thefts of purses, money and jewelry in the trains and in the
subway's 57 stations surged to over 800 cases last year from 30 in
1980. These and other petty crimes were 26.6 times as high last year
as in 1980.
   But officials said Friday that no murder or rape has ever been
committed in the subway system, which is used by 650,000 people each
day.
   Subway vandalism also was reported on the rise. In 1988, the
subway system spent $100,000 repairing damage by graffiti writers
and vandals.
</TEXT>
