<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Spain-Shooting     03-11 0122</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Spain-Shooting,0126</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Civil Guards Slain at Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO DE COMPOSTELA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women and a man armed
with pistols entered a branch of the Bank of Spain in this
northwestern city and killed two Civil Guards, police reported.
   They said the killers fled without taking any money.
   Friday's attack was blamed by police on terrorists of the
left-wing GRAPO organization, but no individual or group asserted
responsibility.
   GRAPO is a Spanish acronym for the 1st of October Revolutionary
Anti-Fascist Group.
   The organization became inactive in the early 1980s after scores
of terrorist assaults but on Oct. 4 two women and a man shot to
death a policeman stationed at a government office in Madrid and
GRAPO claimed responsibility.
</TEXT>
