<DOCNO> AP890311-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay     03-11 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rodriguez Accepts Presidential Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who seized power
in a coup that ousted President Alfredo Stroessner, says he has
agreed to be the presidential nominee of the governing Colorado
Party.
   The elections are set for May 1.
   ``At no moment was I inspired by inferior motives or a hunger for
power,'' Rodriguez said Friday. ``My decision was inspired only in
the happiness of my country and the well-being of all my fellow
citizens.''
   Rodriguez said that if elected, he will work within an
``exemplary multiparty system'' to carry out constitutional reforms
that would give Paraguay ``a respected image.''
   Opposition politicians have called for elimination of a clause in
the constitution that allows a president to continually seek
re-election.
   They also want anulled a 1970 criminal law called the ``defense
of public peace'' that was widely used under Stroessner to harass
dissidents for allegedly doing such things as ``inspiring class
hatred'' among Paraguayans.
   ``The nomination was no surprise,'' said Domingo Laino, president
of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party, Paraguay's largest
opposition group.
   ``Since the 1940s, the Colorado Party has been nominating
generals for the presidency. They seem unable to separate themselves
from men in uniform.''
   Rodriguez, a 65-year-old cavalry general, organized the Feb. 3
coup that ended Stroessner's 34 years in power.
   Meanwhile, former Interior Minister Sabino Augusto Montanaro left
Paraguay for political asylum in Honduras. Montanaro, 66, was given
refuge in the Honduran Embassy in Asuncion the day of the coup. A
telephoned bomb threat delayed his flight for two hours on Friday.
   Montanaro was one of Stroessner's most trusted aides and
president of the Colorado Party.
   He was one of five ministers and seven high government and party
officials accused of ``crimes against public administration'' after
the coup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
