<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial Bjt   03-11 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial, Bjt,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>McFarlane Denies Knowing Many Actions of Subordinate North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former National Security Adviser Robert
McFarlane says he was unaware of many of Oliver North's activities
for the Contras but thought the efforts of a single military officer
would be ``inconsequential.''
   Testifying Friday in North's trial on charges stemming from the
Iran-Contra affair, McFarlane said he didn't know how his former
aide had become involved in private fund-raising for the Contras or
was determining how private contributions were being spent.
   McFarlane also said he hadn't known that North had used a public
relations consultant to get a quick $30,000 donation for the Contras.
   Earlier, McFarlane said former President Reagan knew in 1984 that
arrangements had been made to get $1 million a month from Saudi
Arabia for the the U.S.-backed rebels in Nicaragua.
   And Reagan said ``we'll all be hanging by our thumbs'' if word
got out that McFarlane or other administration officials were
seeking help from abroad at a time that Congress had forbidden
direct U.S. aid to the Contras, according to minutes of the 1984
meeting read into the court record.
   Despite a series of memos from North to McFarlane between
December 1984 and May 1985, McFarlane said he didn't know specifics
of North's activities such as his help in directing the Contras in
opening of another front in Nicaragua.
   ``I had been in the military for 20 years and I knew the
activities of a single officer in setting up a Southern Front was
inconsequential,'' said McFarlane, like North a former Marine. ``It
didn't occur to me that North ... could set up a Southern Front.''
   In the late summer and fall of 1985, two congressional panels
began asking about news reports of North's involvement with the
Contras. Four of North's 12 criminal charges say he prepared
responses for McFarlane's signature essentially denying that North
was doing anything for the guerrilla force.
   McFarlane has pleaded guilty to four charges of withholding
information from Congress and was sentenced last week to two years'
probation, 200 hours of community service and fines of $20,000.
   A March 5, 1985, memo from North to McFarlane says Guatemala
should get extra U.S. aid because Guatemalan officials supplied
phony certificates that permitted a clandestine arms shipment to go
to the Contras.
   ``I didn't even look at the certificates at the time,'' said
McFarlane, saying they were ``one of 10,000 documents'' that crossed
his desk.
   McFarlane said that ``there was a relation'' between the
certificates and the suggestion for additional aid, although the
extra aid ``stood on the merits.'' But the ``fact they helped the
freedom fighters certainly didn't disqualify them'' from getting
additional assistance, McFarlane said.
   The request for extra aid went to top Cabinet officials and the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff without mentioning that phony
end-user certificates had been provided.
   The end-user certificates state that a country, such as
Guatemala, is the ultimate destination of arms.
   A March 16, 1985, memo suggests having a tax-exempt charitable
organization collect private donations that would be used to aid the
Contras, a move that would be illegal.
   McFarlane acknowledged that a tax-exempt organization cannot
raise money for military items for use in a foreign country, but
said that even ``the president suggested that a time or two.''
   In response to a Dec. 4, 1984, memo from North, McFarlane refused
to authorize having the U.S. government let the government of Taiwan
know that the United States supported that nation making a
contribution to the Contras.
   ``I thought the problem ... was our seeking military help from
another country,'' McFarlane testified.
   North is accused of lying during congressional and presidential
inquiries into the Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
