<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Kennedy     03-11 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kennedy,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Kennedy Says He Won't Run For Governor, Announces Separation
From Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II ended speculation he
would run for Massachusetts governor in 1990, saying he did not want
to campaign while serving his congressional district and caring for
his children.
   Kennedy, 36, also announced Friday he was separating from his
wife, Sheilah, and said it was a factor in the decision not to run.
   The eldest son of the late Robert F. Kennedy was considered the
early front-runner for the 1990 race to succeed Massachusetts Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis.
   Kennedy left Boston on Friday for an undisclosed location to
spend the weekend in seclusion with his 8-year-old twins, said Chuck
McDermott, the congressman's top aide and long-time friend.
   ``This has been a very painful day for me and my family,''
Kennedy said in a prepared statement. ``As a father, my principle
obligation and deepest personal desire is to assist my children
through the most difficult time in their lives.
   ``I also have a commitment to serve the people of the 8th
Congressional District. Therefore, I feel it impossible at this time
to take on the added burden of running for another office. To end
any further speculation, I wish to make it clear that I do not
intend to run for governor.''
   Kennedy, the first member of the latest generation of Kennedys to
enter politics, instantly became a powerful fixture in Massachusetts
politics when in 1986 he won the House seat held by his uncle, John
F. Kennedy, and later former House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill Jr.
   Speculation about a gubernatorial run soared when Dukakis, the
failed Democratic presidential nominee, announced in January that he
would not seek a fourth term and Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn said he
would not run for governor.
   In a separate statement on his marriage, Kennedy said he and his
wife decided to separate ``only after long and intense efforts to
find another course.''
   Kennedy married Sheila Brewster Rauch, a banker's daughter and
Philadelphia Main Line debutante, on Feb. 3, 1979. Mrs. Kennedy, 39,
a 1971 graduate of Wheaton College, met Kennedy while she was doing
graduate work at Harvard University.
   The couple had their only children, twins, Joseph Patrick Kennedy
III and Matthew Rauch Kennedy, on Oct. 4, 1980.
</TEXT>
