<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SNOHOMISH, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Today'' show weatherman Willard Scott
might see it as a warming trend from the west _ a blast of good will
from letter-writers who want to help him weather his stormy
relations with host Bryant Gumbel.
   ``A group of us at the office felt Willard might not get a great
shake unless we got together to say we want Willard,'' said Thom
Ris, organizer of the ``We Want Willard'' Campaign.
   Ris was moved to action by reports of a Gumbel memo to NBC brass
that criticized Scott and said he was killing the show with his
``bad taste.''
   ``My feeling is that the people in the networks get kind of
isolated, but there's a real desire for corny, comic relief from
some of the serious stuff we get in the morning,'' Ris said Thursday.
   He said the campaign is aimed at getting 250,000 Scott supporters
to write to NBC on Scott's behalf.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spiritual channeler J.Z. Knight and her estranged
husband, Jeffrey Knight, tried to cut down on their expenses, but
could only get by on slightly less than $40,000 a month, according
to court papers.
   Neither of the Knights is commenting publicly on the breakup, but
their lawyers say the two are working out a settlement agreement.
   Ms. Knight purports to be the medium for a 35,000-year-old spirit
named Ramtha, whose followers include actress Shirley MacLaine, who
has written that she knew Ramtha in a previous incarnation.
   Ms. Knight, one of the first spirit channelers in the New Age
movement, runs seminars in which people pay hundreds of dollars to
hear the pronouncements she delivers in a gruff voice she says
belongs to the spirit.
   According to papers filed for Knight in Pierce County Superior
Court, Ms. Knight has monthly earnings of $240,000 from the Ramtha
seminars.
   Knight said in the court papers that he and his wife had tried to
keep expenses to $20,000 a month, but they couldn't keep below
``$37,000 in any one month as a personal budget _ the bulk of that
being spent on her.''
   Knight asked for a ``small monthly amount'' of $10,000 in a
request for spousal support. A trial date is set for April 8.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Florida Gov. LeRoy Collins,
honored by hundreds of well-wishers on his 80th birthday, says he
has no regrets about the tough decisions he made that may have cost
him politically.
   ``So many times my own conscience was different than what would
say the majority conscience was,'' said Collins, who is credited
with helping the civil rights movement in the 1950s while governor.
``In those times, I stayed with my own conscience. ... Usually it
brought me out fine.''
   Several hundred people, including Collins' wife of 57 years, Mary
Call, and their children and grandchildren, gathered Friday at the
Florida State University Law School Commons to honor the former
governor.
   In 1957, Collins vetoed a bill that would have given school
boards the power to shut down schools rather than admit black
children. The veto was upheld by a slim margin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SLIPPERY ROCK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Clark, the high school principal
whose disciplinary methods are the focus of the film ``Lean on Me,''
says he's not questioning his suspension for arranging an assembly
at which four strippers performed.
   What he does bother him, he said Thursday, is that the Board of
Education in Paterson, N.J., and superintendent are ``puritanical
demogogues.''
   ``For them to get sanctimonious on me,'' Clark said. ``They were
going to suspend somebody. So I said, `You want to suspend somebody,
suspend me. I need a rest. I'm tired and you're going to pay me.'''
   The five-day suspension is to begin Monday.
   The assembly at Eastside High School in New Jersey included an
act by a dancer who stripped four male dancers down to their
G-strings. Clark was not at the school the day of the assembly last
month and has said he never expected the dance group he hired to
lapse into lasciviousness.
   Clark, interviewed during a speaking engagement at Slippery Rock
University, said the controversy over his hard-line disciplinary
methods has followed him since he became principal of Eastside in
1982.
   ``I'm seriously thinking about getting out of education,'' Clark
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Longer version moved on some sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic gold medalist Tim Daggett says
civil liability laws are threatening youth sports programs and could
hurt the United States' ability to compete internationally.
   Daggett, who won a gold medal in 1984 as a U.S. gymnastics team
member, said Friday he does not have to look far to see the impact
of lawsuits on youth sports. His former high school, which named its
gymnasium for him, recently dropped gymnastics because of liability
risks.
   ``That hurts a lot,'' said Daggett, 26, a native of West
Springfield, Mass.
   Daggett was in Green Bay to speak at a reception sponsored in
part by state Sen. Jerome Van Sistine, who has been a proponent of
changing state liability laws.
   ``If we don't dramatically change our civil liability laws, we
could seriously damage our chances to be competitive in all
sports,'' Daggett said.
