<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq     03-11 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Envoy Sees Progress In Iran-Iraq Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. official says Iran and Iraq are
making progress toward breaking their stalemate and agreeing on a
permanent peace in their Persian Gulf war.
   ``We may be on the right track,'' said Swedish U.N. Ambassador
Jan K. Eliasson, the special U.N. envoy to the gulf talks. He would
not discuss specific proposals that have been considered by the two
sides.
   Eliasson met for two days last week with Iranian diplomats led by
a deputy foreign minister, and held meetings Wednesday and Thursday
with the Iraqis, led by U.N. ambassador Ismat Kittani.
   The talks are aimed at arranging a meeting between Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and his Iraqi counterpart, Tariq
Aziz.
   ``We discussed with the parties, at length, both matters of
procedure and matters of substance, and how we are now to best
proceed to make progress,'' Eliasson told reporters.
   ``I would say we are making some progress when it comes to
defining the framework, the shape of the talks, and we hope this
progress will continue and will be evident on the ministerial level,
the political level,'' he said.
   The Iranian and Iraqi foreign ministers were tentatively
scheduled to meet in late March, but Eliasson indicated that
deadline may not be met.
   Since the Moslem month of daytime prayer and fasting, Ramadan,
begins in late March and lasts four weeks, the talks could well be
delayed until May.
   Velayati and Aziz are to meet at an undisclosed location
somewhere near U.N. headquarters to resume the peace talks, which
deadlocked as soon as they began last Aug. 25 in Geneva.
   The talks broke down over Iraq's demand that Iran give up the
right to search ships in international waters for war cargo bound
for Iraq. Tehran has not actually searched any ships since a
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire took effect Aug. 20.
   Baghdad also insists that Iran agree to a plan to have the United
Nations dredge the Shatt al-Arab waterway, Iraq's only outlet to the
sea.
   Tehran insists that the next step in the peace process must be a
withdrawal of troops to their own territory. Iraq still holds about
260 square miles of Iranian territory.
   Tensions along their 740-mile front line are becoming
increasingly tense, especially near an artificial lake Iranian
engineers created as a barrier near the Shatt al-Arab.
   Shelling broke out near the water work on Monday and Tuesday,
according to the office of top U.N. peacekeeper Marrack Goulding.
   Reports of the exchanges sent jitters through the oil markets
Wednesday as a rumor circulated that the war had resumed.
</TEXT>
