<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     03-11 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Free Former Somoza Guards This Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will free nearly 1,900
former members of ousted President Anastasio Somoza's national guard
on March 19, the chief of state security said.
   Commander Lenin Cerna said the jailed guardsmen will be freed
after the National Assembly formally approves a pardon request from
President Daniel Ortega.
   The pardons are the result of agreements signed by Ortega and the
presidents of El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and Costa Rica at a
Feb. 13-14 summit in El Salvador.
   Cerna, who presides over a commission overseeing the releases,
said no restrictions will be placed on the former guardsmen. They
will be free to leave the country, he said Friday.
   Ortega said earlier this week that 41 ex-guardsmen would remain
in jail.
   The president defended the plan to pardon the former guardsmen,
who were jailed after the leftist Sandinistas ousted Somoza in a
1979 revolution.
   Ortega called on Nicaraguans to give guardsmen who are released
``the opportunity to reintegrate themselves into society.''
   ``The guardsman who wants to rejoin society has nothing to
fear,'' Ortega said. But he warned that those who ``return to their
criminal activities'' would face ``popular anger in its full force.''
   The 1,894 prisoners will be released during a ceremony at the
Modelo Prison in Tipitapa, 14 miles west of Managua, Cerna said.
   In their agreement, the region's presidents also said they will
draft a plan by May 15 to dismantle the 11,000-member Nicaraguan
rebel army. The rebels, known as Contras, fled to Honduras after
U.S. military assistance ended last year.
   The United States began supporting the Contras in 1981. The
Sandinista government and the rebels signed a provisional truce in
March 1988, but talks on a permanent cease-fire have broken down.
</TEXT>
