<DOCNO> AP890311-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0455EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh     03-11 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Border Troops Alert For Possible Chakma Rebel Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bangladesh placed troops on alert along
the Indian border to guard against attacks by Buddhist rebel
tribesmen, military sources in the region said today.
   The sources in the Chittagong Hill Tracts in southeastern
Bangladesh said they had received reports that rebels from the
Chakma tribe were planning raids from sanctuaries in India.
   India has repeatedly denied the rebels have sanctuaries on its
side of the border.
   The Bangladeshi sources, who were contacted by telephone and
spoke on condition of anonymity, also said India had placed its own
military troops on alert along the border.
   An Indian government spokesman in New Delhi called the report ``a
load of rubbish.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The rebels have been fighting a bush war against the Bangladeshi
government in an effort to win autonomy for the region and push out
Moslem settlers. More than 3,000 people have been killed since the
revolt began in 1974.
   On Feb. 28, the Bangladeshi government passed legislation to give
the hill tracts limited autonomy in an effort to end the insurgency.
Under the new law, hill tract residents would elect local councils
with the powers to administer and develop the region, appoint police
and maintain law and order.
   The military sources said the anticipated rebel offensive may be
an effort to sabotage the government's peace plan in an effort to
win greater autonomy.
   Chakmas make up about 75 percent of the 800,000 people living in
the hill tracts. At one point the number of Moslem Bengali settlers
reached 300,000, but in 1985 President Hussain Muhammad Ershad
banned further Moslem migration to the area.
   The number of settlers declined as the Chakmas continued their
attacks. Western diplomats have estimated only about 100,000
settlers remain. Some other Buddhist tribes also live in the region.
   The area is impoverished but has unexploited pockets of natural
gas. Efforts to survey and tap the gas in the early 1970s were
halted because of rebel attacks.
   The region is one of the few parts of Bangladesh that generally
remains above water during perennial floods in the densely populated
nation of 110 million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
