<FIRST>r a PM-MarcosIndictment     03-11 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Indictment,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Allegations Lodged Against Marcoses in Superseding Indictment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Additional allegations of fraudulent activities
have been leveled against former Philippines President Ferdinand E.
Marcos and his wife, Imelda, by a federal grand jury in Manhattan.
   In a superseding indictment made public Friday, the Marcoses were
accused of illegally funneling an additional $77 million into this
country.
   Missing from the new indictment was the name of Panamanian lawyer
Jaime Alberto Arias, who originally was charged with obstructing
justice and mail fraud.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Debra Livingston declined to comment on
why the 54-year-old Arias was not listed or say if he was
cooperating with prosecutors.
   Except for the Marcoses, all of the other defendants had been
classified as fugitives. Among the remaining defendants in the case
are Saudi Arabian businessman and arms dealer Adnan Khashoggi.
   The Marcoses, living in exile in Honolulu since fleeing the
Philippines three years ago, were indicted for an alleged
racketeering conspiracy in October.
   That indictment, which named eight co-defendants as well as a
California bank, accused the Marcoses of plundering more than $100
million from their homeland's treasury to buy choice Manhattan real
estate and expensive artworks.
   The new allegations, while not adding any more counts to the
six-count indictment, accused the Marcoses and other co-conspirators
of fraudulently bringing to this country an additional $65 million
allegedly stolen from the Philippines.
   The source of an additional $12 million in stolen funds cited in
the 90-page superseding indictment was not explained.
   ``I don't know how this helps or hurts the government's case. I
suppose they're refining the charges because they suppose the
leading defendant will not be available,'' Marcos attorney John J.
Tigue said.
   The defense has contended that Marcos, 71, who suffers from
heart, lung and kidney ailments, is dying. He remains hospitalized
in Honolulu.
   ``We are as prepared as ever to defend against the charges in the
superseding indictment,'' Tigue said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
