<FIRST>r a PM-People-BonJovi     03-11 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Bon Jovi,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bon Jovi Caught Trespassing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jon Bon Jovi, lead singer of a rock band that hit
the big time two years ago with the album ``Slippery When Wet,''
wasn't quite slick enough when caught trespassing on a closed
skating rink in Central Park.
   Bon Jovi, 27, of Rumson, N.J., his girlfriend and another couple
were handcuffed by a parks department patrol officer and taken to
the Central Park Precinct station house early Friday morning, police
said.
   They were given summonses for trespassing at Wollman Rink and
released within an hour, leaving plenty of time for Bon Jovi to
perform at a sold-out concert Friday night at the Nassau Coliseum.
   A spokesman for the group said Bon Jovi, who was booked under his
real name, John Bongiovi, and the rest of the band were off Thursday
night and Bon Jovi and his friends left their room in the
Ritz-Carlton Hotel to take a carriage ride in Central Park.
   When they couldn't find a hansom cab, they decided to go ice
skating in their shoes and sneakers.
</TEXT>
