<FIRST>r p PM-Quayle     03-11 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Decries `New McCarthyism' in Tower Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle, saying Americans
``won't condone a new wave of McCarthyism,'' harshly criticized some
of his former Senate colleagues over the failed nomination of John
Tower to be secretary of defense.
   ``I think virtually every objective observer of Senate
proceedings in this matter has been deeply troubled by the `raw
sewage,' as one Republican senator termed it, that has spilled into
the Senate chamber in the form of excerpts from FBI reports and
unsubstantiated anecdotes repeated for public consumption,'' Quayle
said in a speech in Indianapolis Friday.
   ``Everyone understands this is not politics as usual, that this
is trial and conviction by rumor and is a violation of the standards
of decency,'' said Quayle. ``We will not condone a new wave of
McCarthyism in this country.''
   Tower, burdened by reports of alcohol abuse and womanizing, was
rejected by the Senate as secretary of defense 53-47 Thursday. On
Friday, President Bush announced he selected Rep. Richard Cheney,
R-Wyo., as the new nominee for defense secretary.
   Asked about Quayle's remarks, Bush said in Washington: ``I
haven't seen what he said so I can't tell you whether he speaks for
me. I speak for myself. He speaks for himself.''
   However, Bush said he understands why Quayle feels the way he
does.
   In Washington, responding to Quayle's remarks, Sen. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., said: ``I fought Sen. Joe McCarthy in the 1950s,
when Dan Quayle was still in kindergarten. I can inform the vice
president that he is using the same tactic Joe McCarthy used:
guilty-by-association.''
   Three times during his 25-minute speech, Quayle said the Tower
debate recalled the 1950s, when Republican Sen. Joseph McCarthy of
Wisconsin used innuendo and trumped-up charges to accuse people of
having ties to communism.
   Quayle, a 42-year-old former Indiana senator making his first
trip home since becoming vice president, said allegations based on
rumor and innuendo shouldn't be used to tear down the reputation of
a public figure.
   Asked at a news conference if he believed a Senate debate on one
public figure amounted to a trend toward McCarthy tactics, Quayle
said, ``What I'm doing is just putting out a warning that if they're
going to rely on this kind of information for denying people a
position in the cabinet, we will not condone it nor will the
American people.''
   Quayle, speaking to 1,500 people at a luncheon meeting of the
Economic Club of Indianapolis, also said the rejection of Tower's
nomination signals a legislative attack on the power of the
presidency.
   ``Why has the Tower affair evoked such intense feelings?'' Quayle
said. ``I think it's because every Republican senator understands
that it is not just the Bush administration that is under attack. It
happens to be the constitutional prerogatives of the executive
branch.''
   Quayle said he had never ``encountered such anger and bitterness
in the Senate chamber'' as he did Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
