<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     03-11 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Militia Clashes With Christian Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian units of the Lebanese army
clashed today with Syrian-backed Moslem militias in Beirut's
abandoned commercial district.
   Police said no casualities were reported from the exchanges of
machine gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades. The sporadic battled
erupted late Friday and continued intermittently into this morning.
   Hostilities broke out Wednesday between Christian army units and
Druse militiamen in hills southeast of Beirut and spread to Beirut's
bomb-scarred old commercial district straddling the city's harbor.
   By police count four people were killed and 15 wounded in the
escalation of tension, which followed a decision by Christian army
commander Gen. Michel Aoun to prevent commercial ships from docking
at militia-run ports.
   Aoun's naval force has seized at least two commercial ships
heading to a port south of Beirut run by Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party militia.
   Aoun's move aims at stripping the private armies of their revenue
which they make mainly from the illegal ports.
   But this step was rejected by Jumblatt and other Syrian-backed
Moslem leaders, who vowed to bombard Beirut port in retaliation.
   Aoun also heads the Christian cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government.
</TEXT>
