<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Reed     03-11 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Reed,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former GE And Federal Reserve Bank Chairman Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RYE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip D. Reed, a former General Electric Co.
chairman who served in a series of assignments for the federal
government during World War II, died at his suburban New York home.
He was 89.
   Reed, who became a director of the Federal Reserve Bank of New
York after retiring from GE in 1958, died Friday after a long
illness.
   He joined GE in 1926 and became chairman of the board at age 40.
Among the posts he held during World War II, when he left the
company temporarily, was chief of the U.S. Mission for Economic
Affairs in London.
   After the war, he led the company's conversion back to production
of consumer goods from the manufacture of military equipment.
   Following his retirement, Reed spent seven years at the Federal
Reserve Bank, six as chairman, and also served on the boards of
numerous other companies.
   He is survived by two children, Philip Jr. of Princeton, N.Y.,
and Kathryn Reed Smith of Davis, Calif; four grandchildren and seven
great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
