<SECOND>PM-BRF--SAfrica-Police,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Policemen Sentenced To Prison In Activist's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISHO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six police officers from a black
homeland have been sentenced to prison in the killing of Eric
Mntonga, a black activist who died after a brutal interrogation.
   Mntonga's body was found in the nominally independent homeland of
Ciskei on July 25, 1987. A day earlier, according to testimony, he
was assaulted during interrogation at a Ciskei police station. No
testimony was offered that Mntonga, 35, had committed any offense.
   Two generals from Ciskei's security police unit, who were accused
of ordering a cover-up after being informed of Mntonga's death, were
sentenced Friday to two-year prison terms.
   Sentences ranging from four to 12 years were issued to four other
policemen, including a major and a colonel. They were convicted of
culpable homicide and defeating the ends of justice.
