<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OrganDonorTrial     03-11 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Organ Donor Trial,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Parents $600,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple was awarded $600,000 by a jury
that ruled doctors at a university hospital acted recklessly in
removing organs from the couple's brain-dead son without permission.
   The Monongalia County Circuit Court jury deliberated for just
over two hours Friday before awarding Ronald and Carolyn Crawford of
New Freeport, Pa., $500,000 in compensatory damages and $100,000 in
punitive damages.
   The Crawfords had asked for $400,000 in their lawsuit against the
state Board of Regents, which ran the hospital _ then called West
Virginia University Medical Center, now WVU Hospitals Inc. _ at the
time of Adam Crawford's death on July 27, 1984.
   ``For once in my life, I've seen justice done,'' said Mrs.
Crawford, a 44-year-old coal miner. ``I can't tell you how happy I
am.''
   ``I would have won even if they didn't award us anything,'' added
Crawford, 48, a disabled former truck driver.
   ``That hospital will never do anything like this again. That's
all I wanted from the beginning.''
   George McLaughlin, a Wheeling attorney who represented the
regents, declined comment.
   Adam Crawford, 17, became ill July 19, 1984, while playing
basketball at a camp near Waynesburg, Pa. He was taken to the WVU
Medical Center, where he was pronounced dead eight days later after
suffering a brain aneurysm.
   The Crawfords denied the contention by hospital officials that
the couple had given their permission to remove the youth's organs.
</TEXT>
