<FIRST>r a PM-MultipleKillings     03-11 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Killings,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Supreme Court Clears Way For Simmons Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prison officials began preparing for the
execution of convicted mass murderer R. Gene Simmons after the state
Supreme Court ruled he was competent to waive his right to appeal
his death sentence.
   Friday's ruling clears the way for Simmons to become the first
person to be executed in Arkansas in 25 years.
   Simmons is to die by lethal injection Thursday for the December
1987 slayings of 14 family members. Their bodies were found in his
home and on his property near Dover, Ark., about 75 miles northwest
of Little Rock.
   Simmons, 48, was sentenced to death last month by Circuit Judge
John Patterson. He was convicted and sentenced to death last May for
two other deaths that occurred during his 1987 shooting rampage.
   The state Supreme Court ruling came one day after Simmons asked
the court to expedite its review of his competency to waive appeals
from last month's conviction.
   ``After a careful review of the record and exhibits, we affirm
the trial court's decision that the petitioner has knowingly and
intelligently waived his right to appeal,'' the court said in a
three-page opinion.
   Simmons asked that no one interfere in the case after an
execution date was set in his first trial. He said the sentence was
just, pleading, ``Let the torture and suffering in me end.''
   Edith Nesby, sister of Rebecca, Simmons' wife, told The
Associated Press by telephone from her home in Briggsdale, Colo: ``I
think this is one of the few times that Gene and I agree that
justice is being served.''
   David White, a spokesman for the state Correction Department,
said preparations for an execution usually begin about one week
prior to the execution date.
   White said prison officials have to ensure that the execution
chamber is in working order and that the director must choose
executioners and witnesses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
