<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-11 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Coast Dampened By Rain; Much Of Rest Of Nation Stays Dry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A subtropical flow of warm, moist air extended today from Hawaii
to the Oregon and northern California coasts, which were pelted by
showers and thundershowers while much of the rest of the nation
stayed dry.
   More than 2 inches of rain fell at Ben Lomond, Calif., as the
storms spread along much of the upper West Coast on Friday.
   Areas in the northern Sierra Nevada have received 4 inches of
rain since Thursday afternoon, and heavy rains have kept the
Sacramento River above the flood warning stage near Colusa.
   Winds gusted late Friday evening over western Nevada, with
clockings of 59 mph at Reno and to 64 mph at Stead, north of Reno.
   The remainder of the nation had predominately dry weather this
morning, but snowshowers fell in eastern upper Michigan. Sault Ste.
Marie, Mich., got another inch Friday night, giving the city a total
of 27 inches on the ground.
   Still, a sampling of spring continued across the central and
southern Plains, with temperatures in the low- to mid-60s from
western Kansas into the southern plains of Texas this morning.
   Record highs for the date on Friday were set in 34 cities in the
West and Southwest, and the nation's high was 97 at Tucson, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for rainshowers widespread in the Pacific
Northwest and scattered in northern and central California into the
northern Plateau; rain or snowshowers in Montana, northern New York
state and northern Vermont; an drainshowers widely scattered from
North Dakota into upper Michigan.
   Predicted highs were 30s and 40s from northern Montana across
North Dakota and Minnesota to northern Michigan, and from New York
state to northern New England; 70s in Florida, the central Gulf
coastal states and the lower half of the Mississippi valley; 70s and
80s from the southern Plains across the southern Rockies to Southern
California; 90s in southern Arizona, southwest Oklahoma and parts of
Texas.
   Elsewhere, highs were expected to reach the 50s and 60s.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 2 degrees at
Houlton, Maine, to 74 at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 47 fair; Boston 27 fair; Buffalo 32 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 39 fair; Cincinnati 37 fair; Cleveland 33 fair;
Detroit 29 fair; Miami 53 fair; New York 28 fair; Philadelphia 26
fair; Pittsburgh 34 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 18 fair;
Washington 31 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 32 fair; Chicago 39 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 49
fair; Denver 46 partly cloudy; Des Moines 40 foggy; Indianapolis 36
fair; Kansas City 48 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 32 foggy; Nashville
42 fair; New Orleans 48 fair; St. Louis 46 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 50 fair; Anchorage 20 fair; Las Vegas 68
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 55 foggy; Phoenix 69 fair; Salt Lake City
55 partly cloudy; San Diego 58 cloudy; San Francisco 59 rain;
Seattle 58 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 21 cloudy; Toronto 30 cloudy.
</TEXT>
