<FIRST>r a PM-Aliens-Corruption     03-11 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aliens-Corruption,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says INS Memos Reveal Vice Among Mexican Authorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal probe has found evidence that
Mexican authorities extorted money from aliens headed for the United
States, leading some smugglers to alter their routes, a newspaper
reported.
   The alleged corruption was described in three internal U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service memos dated Feb. 22 and Feb.
23, The Brownsville Herald reported Friday.
   The memos were written by E.M. Trominski, INS district director
in Mexico City, to the Office of Foreign Operations in Washington,
D.C.
   One memo quoted an INS special agent working in Matamoros, across
the border from Brownsville, as saying: ``The bus depot is being
worked by Mexican Customs and other agencies, all on the take. The
bribe situation has caused the smugglers to off-load groups outside
of Matamoros and to get them downtown by other means, avoiding the
bus station.''
   Border Patrol intelligence officers in South Texas and Silvestre
Reyes, sector chief in McAllen, failed to return repeated phone
calls.
   Verne Jervis, INS spokesman in Washington, said he was unaware of
any INS agents operating in Mexico. ``To do that, you have to get
permission of the host country,'' he told the newspaper.
   The memos addressed activities of INS anti-smuggling teams in 10
Mexican cities, Guatemala and El Salvador, detailing techniques used
by alien smugglers and steps taken by INS agents in Mexico to
infiltrate smuggling operations.
   ``Major smugglers are chartering buses'' to move aliens, one memo
stated. ``The buses reportedly stay away from the federal highways
because of fear of `ripoffs''' by Mexican authorities, using back
roads instead, it said.
   One memo said a group of 38 Guatemalans and 1 Salvadoran was
``ripped off in the amount of 5 M (million) pesos ($2,100) by the
Federal Highway police who then called the municipal police.''
   A cable from San Salvador ``had specific information regarding
alien smuggling by air from San Salvador to Tapachula (Mexico),''
one memo said. ``The information was specific, including names of
pilots and aircraft tail numbers.''
   Trominksi wrote, ``I gave my personal observation that, if true,
such an operation could not take place without some sort of
`official' help.''
   Two memos also reported that Mexican Immigration Director General
Susana Torres Hernandez was concerned that the recent policy to
immediately detain illegal aliens in South Texas might leave large
numbers of undocumented Central Americans stranded in Mexico,
straining the country's scarce social services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
