<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     03-11 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korean Armed Forces Put On Alert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea today put its armed forces on alert
because of what it called the danger of war posed by the U.S.-South
Korea military exercises that begin next week.
   The North's official Korean Central News Agency, monitored in
Tokyo, said President Kim Il Sung issued the order and warned that
if the United States and South Korea ``dare provoke a war against
us, our revolutionary armed forces and entire people will turn out
as one in the fight to defend the sacred fatherland.''
   About 200,000 U.S. and South Korean troops are expected to take
part in the 10-day annual joint exercises called ``Team Spirit''
scheduled to begin on Tuesday in the South.
   North Korea has demanded a halt to the exercises, calling them a
preparation for a nuclear attack on the North. U.S. and South Korean
officials say the exercises are defensive and vital to South Korea's
security.
   North Korea has issued similar orders in the past at the time of
the annual exercises.
   ``The (North) Korean people love peace but do not want
confrontation and war,'' the news agency said. ``But we will never
allow any attempt of the U.S. imperialists and the South Korean
puppet clique to threaten and provoke us at random.''
   South Korea estimates North Korea's military manpower at 870,000,
compared to 650,000 in the South.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into the communist North and the
capitalist South at the end of World War II in 1945, when U.S. and
Soviet troops ended Japan's colonial rule over the region. The two
Koreas have remained enemies since the 1950-53 Korean War.
</TEXT>
