<FIRST>r a PM-OdorEmergency     03-11 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Odor Emergency,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Smell Diverts Flight, But Is Traced to Passenger's Pants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a Braniff Airways flight
made an emergency landing and all 47 passengers slid down chutes
after people smelled gasoline on board _ but the odor was later
traced to a man's pants leg.
   Without warning from the pilot, Flight 796 to Orlando made an
abrupt 180-degree turn about 30 minutes after taking off from
Southwest Florida Regional Airport in Fort Myers on Friday,
passengers said.
   ``The stewardesses were all frantic. They kept running in and out
of the cockpit on our way back,'' said Trish Merkel of Fort Myers.
   Passengers said the plane flew so low returning to the airport
that cars below them looked almost life-size. And the plane's
landing was as abrupt as its turnaround, some said.
   ``I thought we had gone too far and overshot the runway the way
we stopped,'' said Eric Swanson, 20, of Chicago. ``He really hit the
brakes hard and stopped us fast.''
   Forty-seven passengers used emergency slides to escape. But
firefighters called to the plane realized within minutes that the
gasoline smell had come from a passenger's pants.
   ``Apparently one of the men on board had spilled some gas on
himself while he was filling up his car before the flight,'' said
Braniff spokeswoman Sandy Smith, who declined to identify the
passenger.
</TEXT>
