<FIRST>r i PM-Earthquakes     03-11 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earthquakes,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquakes Shake Tokyo, Turkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two earthquakes shook the Tokyo area today, but
there were no immediate reports of serious damage or injuries.
   Central Meteorological Agency officials said an registering 5 on
the Richter scale hit the area at 4:12 p.m. It was 25 miles below
ground in southern Ibaragi prefecture, about 60 miles northeast of
Tokyo.
   Earlier in the day, a weaker earthquake struck north of Tokyo in
Tochigi prefecture, the agency said.
   That quake registered 3 in the city of Nikko on the Japanese
scale that goes to 7. No Richter reading was available.
   The quake rattled windows and doors in Nikko, forecasters said.
   Agency officials said that quake's epicenter was 75 miles north
of Tokyo at a depth of six miles.
   In Turkey on Friday, an earthquake rocked the eastern Anatolian
provinces of Erzurum, Van and Kars, destroying some homes but no
causing no casualties, state radio reported.
   The broadcast said that quake, measuring 4.2 on the Richter
scale, hit the area at 10 a.m.
   It said the quake destroyed 10 homes and left cracks in the walls
of 120 houses in villages in Erzurum.
   The Richter scale measures the magnitude of an earthquake. Each
increase of one digit represents a tenfold increase in strength. A
quake with a magnitudee of 5 can cause considerable damage in
populated areas and a quake registering 4 can cause moderate damage.
   The Japanese scale measures ground motion at particular locations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890311-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RodinTheft     03-11 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rodin Theft,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Suspect in Theft of Rodin Sculpture</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Shih is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police recovered a stolen Rodin sculpture
from the basement of a downtown building a day after arresting a man
for the theft.
   ``Mask of the Man with the Broken Nose,'' a 10-inch tall bust
done by Auguste Rodin 125 years ago and valued at more than $75,000,
was found Friday wrapped in brown paper under a tarpaulin hidden
beneath a sewer line in the basement, police said. It wasn't damaged.
   ``Isn't it wonderful? You never believe that it could happen,''
said Robert Montgomery Scott, president and chief executive officer
of the Philadelphia Museum of Art, which oversees the Rodin Museum.
   ``The theft, you never want to have happen, but the recovery is
the really exciting thing.''
   The discovery came one day after police arrested Stephen W. Shih,
24. He was charged with stealing the bust at gunpoint on Nov. 23
after firing a warning shot and shackling three museum guards
together.
   Shih was awaiting arraignment on charges of robbery, theft,
unlawful restraint, simple assault and weapons offenses, Capt.
William Demski said.
   Police and FBI agents found the bust in the basement of the
building where Shih's mother lives. Police arrested Shih near the
building Thursday after receiving an anonymous tip linking him with
the theft.
   Police don't plan to charge Shih's mother, Capt. Thomas McGinty
said.
   The museum's insurer had offered a $10,000 reward for information
leading to the sculpture's recovery, but Scott said no one has
claimed it.
</TEXT>
