<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WrongBabies     03-11 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wrong Babies,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infants-Parents Reunited After Hospital Confirms Mothers Got Wrong
Babies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosetta Kirks had been nursing her newborn son
for three weeks when she noticed he looked small. Then she realized
she'd been given the wrong infant.
   Today, she's back home with her real 9-pound son, Nicolas.
   ``I'm sure this is the right one,'' a beaming Ms. Kirks, 30, of
Inglewood, said Friday night as she cradled the boy. ``I'm just glad
to have my baby back.''
   Genetic tests completed earlier Friday confirmed Nicolas was Ms.
Kirks' son and that she had received the wrong infant when she left
the maternity ward at Kaiser Permanente Medical Center.
   ``Based on our own investigation and corroborating blood tests,
it appears that two infants were in fact discharged to the wrong
sets of parents,'' said Kaiser spokeswoman Janice Seib.
   The hospital was investigating the apparent mix-up and reviewing
its procedures, Ms. Seib said.
   ``Both families and infants have gone home with the right
people,'' she said. ``As far as we're concerned, that's it.''
   But the attorney for Ms. Kirks and Tommy Milligan, the father,
told reporters he will work to see such mix-ups don't occur again at
Kaiser.
   ``Something's wrong or faulty. Nobody should be put through what
those people have been put through. The hospital shouldn't have done
that,'' said attorney Jerome J. Eisenberg.
   The other parents, identified as Nicholas and Firdowsa Amad
Mallet of Baldwin Hills, couldn't be reached for comment. Hospital
officials said they wanted privacy.
   Both babies were born at Kaiser on Feb. 11.
   Ms. Kirks became suspicious last Sunday when she looked at a
photograph taken just after her son's birth and noticed the infant
she was caring for seemed smaller, said Gene Murphy, a spokesman for
Eisenberg.
   ``That baby had chubby cheeks, and the one she had at home had
`itty bitty' cheeks,'' Murphy said.
   Ms. Kirks' son was 21 inches long and weighed 9 pounds, 3 ounces
at birth, said Shelly Shellmire, another spokesman for Eisenberg.
The baby Ms. Kirk had gone home with initially was 18 inches long
and weighed 6 pounds, she said.
   ``She got nervous,'' Shellmire said. ``She went to the dresser
and got the baby's arm band and discovered that it had a different
name on the arm band.''
   The mother then took the baby back to Kaiser and asked for her
son.
   Blood typing, chromosome studies and DNA typing confirmed the
babies' identities.
   Hospital officials said they wouldn't speculate how the mix-up
occurred until the investigation was completed.
   ``The policies and procedures that we have in place at this time
are in accordance with numerous regulating and governing agencies.
We are confident that they are in every way adequate and
appropriate. We are reviewing adherence to those policies,'' Ms.
Seib said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
