<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Church     03-11 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Church,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Main White Church Declares Apartheid A Sin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main church of the ruling
white Afrikaners for the first time has declared apartheid a sin and
expressed guilt over its role in promoting racial segregation, a
church leader said today.
   The black and mixed-race branches of the Dutch Reformed Church
praised the admission, but said the mother church must act to bring
down apartheid.
   ``We confess with humility and sorrow the participation of our
church in the introduction and legitimation of the ideology of
apartheid and the subsequent suffering of people,'' the white branch
of the Dutch Reformed Church said.
   ``(Apartheid) cannot be accepted on Christian ethical grounds,
because it contravenes the very essence of reconciliation,
neighborly love and righteousness,'' it said.
   It is the most explicit condemnation of South Africa's system of
legal race discrimination made by the white branch of the church. In
1986, the church reversed its decades-old support of segregation and
said apartheid was a mistake, but stopped short of calling it a sin
or heresy.
   The statement was released late Friday after a weeklong meeting
between the white and black and mixed-race branches of the church.
   The black and mixed-race branches welcomed the statement, but
said strong differences with the mother church remain.
   ``It is encouraging that there are ministers in the (white) DRC
that call for fundamental and comprehensive changes,'' said the
black and mixed-race churches. ``But it is vital that they should
embark on acts of liberation within church and society.''
   They called on the white church to condemn specific apartheid
laws and ``develop a theology counteracting apartheid.''
   Piet Roussouw, chief executive of the white church, said today
such issues would be addressed at a meeting next week.
   ``The important thing is that we are working together to address
the problem of discrimination and suffering,'' Roussouw said.
   The Dutch Reformed Church is by far the largest and most
influential church among South Africa's 5 million whites. It counts
President P.W. Botha and virtually all his Cabinet ministers among
its congregants, giving it considerable influence in national
policy. About 1.1 million of the nation's 28 million blacks are
members of the black branch, and 680,000 of the 3 million mixed-race
people belong to their branch.
   In 1986, the white church opened membership to all races, but few
non-whites responded. There are a handful of white church ministers
who serve black congregations, and a few blacks occasionally attend
services in churches of the white branch.
   The church provided the scriptural foundations for apartheid when
the governing National Party came to power in 1948 and began
codifying racial segregation. D.F. Malan, the prime minister from
1948-54 when most apartheid laws were enacted, was a minister in the
church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890311-0058 </DOCNO>
