<HEAD>O'Connor Undergoing Surgery At Emory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with O'Connor in surgery; Picks
up 4th graf, ``The angiogram ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Carroll O'Connor, best known for his role as
blue-collar bigot Archie Bunker in television's ``All in the
Family,'' underwent heart bypass surgery today.
   The surgery was ordered Friday after a routine physical
examination at Emory University Hospital indicated the need for a
coronary artery bypass operation, Maggie Begley, the actor's
publicist, said in Los Angeles.
   Hospital officials announced this morning that O'Connor's surgery
had begun; further details on his immediate condition were not
available.
   The 64-year-old O'Connor, now the star of ``In the Heat of the
Night,'' was admitted Friday to the hospital for a coronary
angiogram.
   ``The angiogram was requested because of a positive stress test
during a routine physical examination by his physician in Covington,
Ga., where Mr. O'Connor has been filming,'' spokeswoman Judy Smith
said in the statement.
   O'Connor, who stars as Police Chief Bill Gillespie on NBC-TV's
``In the Heat of the Night,'' was accompanied to the hospital by his
wife, Nancy.
   ``Carroll is in great spirits and is resting comfortably,'' she
said Friday night.
   David Gerber, chairman of MGM-UA Television, the show's
producers, said studio officials would meet this weekend to
determine how the program would deal with O'Connor's hospitalization.
   Gerber said, however, that production of the popular show was
proceeding as usual. He said 18 of the planned 22 episodes already
had been completed.
   ``All in the Family'' was bounced from network to network and
went through several pilots before CBS-TV finally put it on the air
in January 1971.
   O'Connor played Archie Bunker in the 1970s hit ``All in the
Family,'' a trailblazing comedy that took a satirical look at
bigotry.
