<FIRST>r i PM-Zimbabwe     03-11 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zimbabwe,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Minister Resigns in Black Market Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Enos Nkala has resigned
from the Cabinet over his involvement in black market sales of motor
vehicles.
   He is the second Cabinet minister to quit since a commission
began investigating sales of locally assembled vehicles to senior
government officials who allegedly sold them at illegally inflated
prices.
   Nkala told a three-member commission Friday that he handed his
resignation to acting President Simon Muzenda the previous day.
   To thunderous applause from the packed High Court room, Nkala
said he did this ``when it became clear to me what was going to
happen here, and to show you the gravity with which I treat the
matter.''
   Earlier, Nkala had testified to the commission that his wife,
Thandiwe, had sold a Toyota Cressida on his behalf for the statutory
price of $14,500. But the buyer and Mrs. Nkala on Thursday testified
the car actually was sold illegally for $45,000.
   Nkala told Judge President Wilson Sandura he also has tendered
his resignation from all posts in the governing Zimbabwe African
National Union. As treasurer, Nkala was fourth in the party
hierarchy.
   The minister told the judge that Muzenda had not accepted his
resignations immediately, but was holding them for President Robert
Mugabe's return from a visit to Europe.
   Frederick Shava, the minister of state for political affairs,
resigned Tuesday after admitting he lied to the commission.
   He was the first casualty of the commission instigated by Mugabe
to investigate irregular sales of cars by a local assembly plant to
politicians, military chiefs, civil servants and business executives.
   He also is the first government minister to resign under a cloud
since Mugabe led the white-ruled British colony of Rhodesia to
independence as black-governed Zimbabwe nine years ago.
   The ministers' departure strengthens many critics' charges that
high-level corruption is widespread.
   Shava and Nkala were among six ministers to testify before the
commission about buying cars and trucks from Willowvale Motor
Industries Pvt. Ltd. and then allegedly selling them for fat profits
above fixed retail prices.
   Zimbabwe has a brisk black market in vehicles which are in short
supply because of foreign currency shortages.
   The other ministers denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
