<SECOND>PM-Korea,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Again Denies Involvement In KAL Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea said today the trial of a woman who
confessed to planting a bomb on board a South Korean airliner that
disappeared in 1987 was an attempt to dampen South Korean desires
for reunification.
   ``We have already made it clear that we have nothing to do with
the incident,'' the North's official Korean Central News Agency said
in a report monitored in Tokyo.
   The report was the first North Korean reaction to the trial in
Seoul, South Korea, of a woman identified as Kim Hyon Hui.
   She has confessed to being a North Korean agent and placing a
bomb on the Korean Air Boeing 707 before it disappeared near Burma
over the Andaman Sea in November 1987. All 115 people aboard are
presumed to have died.
   The trial began Tuesday, and the North Korean news agency said
prosecutors ``only repeated the old plot full of contradictions
which they had used several times to shift the blame for the KAL
incident onto us in a far-fetched way.''
   It did not explain the contradictions.
   Through the trial, South Korean officials ``seek an aim of
emasculating the South Korean people's sentiments for
reunification'' with the North, the report said.
   After the plane disappeared, the woman and a companion, an
elderly man, were arrested in Bahrain. They attempted to commit
suicide by taking cyanide hidden in cigarettes. The man died, but
the woman recovered and was extradited to Seoul.
   The woman told the court that Kim Jong Il, son and political heir
of North Korean President Kim Il Sung, had ordered her to blow up
the plane.
