<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0475 03-11 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uprising Cost Israel $666 Million In 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads 4 grafs to UPGRADE attribution with Yaacobi aide, CORRECTS
Yaacobi title. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``In a ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestinian uprising in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip cost Israel's economy $666 million in 1988, an
aide to Communications Minister Gad Yaacobi said today.
   Yaacobi blamed the losses mainly on greater military spending, an
increase in army reserve duty, a drop in production and tourism, and
difficulties in attracting foreign investment, said spokewoman Naama
Henig.
   ``He also warned that the costs to the economy might be at the
same level this year,'' Ms. Henig said. Yaacobi, a member of the
left-leaning Labor Party, was economics minister until November,
when he became communications minister.
   The uprising-related costs nearly wiped out Israel's economic
growth, initially forecast at 2.5 percent, Israel radio quoted
Yaacobi as saying. Instead, Israel's $35 billion economy grew by 1
percent in 1988, considerably less than the 5 percent in 1987.
   In a related development, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin was
quoted as saying today he decided to shift the burden of putting
down the uprising from reserve soldiers to regular troops and
specially trained border police units.
   ``We want to reach a situation where reserve soldiers serve a
maximum of 44 days a year, instead of many now serving 62 days,''
Rabin said on Israel radio.
   The interview was broadcast a day after the army shifted some of
its troops out of Gaza Strip refugee camps in an effort to reduce
tension and fatal clashes.
   The redeployment also came as Foreign Minister Moshe Arens left
for a 10-day visit to the United States where he was expected to
counter pressure to reduce friction in the occupied lands.
   Rabin denied that the redeployment was designed to appease the
United States, saying the main objective was to ``reduce the burden
on the reserve soldiers.''
   Paying for thousands of reserves is proving costly. The Defense
Ministry has estimated the cost of combating the uprising is about
$14 million a month.
   The uprising has also hurt tourism, with only about 1.3 million
tourists entering the country in 1988, down 14 percent from the
previous year. Israeli officials had expected 1988 to be a banner
year because of the state's 40th anniversary celebrations.
   Production was hurt because as many 30,000 of the 110,000
Palestinians employed in Israel have quit their jobs.
   At the same time, the sale of Israeli goods to the territories
fell 70 percent in 1988 to about $140 million, according to the
Industry Ministry.
</TEXT>
