<FIRST>u i AM-Botha Bjt   03-11 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha, Bjt,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ailing President Abandoned by His Party as He Clings to Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since a recent stroke,
President P.W. Botha has lost his stature as the domineering master
of South African politics. Suddenly, he is depicted as a tragic
figure, clinging to power against the wishes of former loyalists.
   Those who have done Botha's bidding for a decade now are engaged
in a concerted campaign to push him into retirement. Botha signaled
his intention to fight back, but there has been a dramatic lack of
public support for the man whose tough tactics earned him the
nickname ``The Great Crocodile.''
   The result, for the moment, is a power struggle between Botha and
his heir apparent, Education Minister F.W. de Klerk.
   De Klerk took over as leader of the governing National Party when
Botha resigned that post Feb. 2, two weeks after his stroke.
   Since then, de Klerk has consolidated his support among
Nationalist members of Parliament and has made no move to disavow
reports he wants Botha to quit the presidency.
   Botha, 73, struck back last week by announcing he planned to
return to work March 15, two weeks earlier than expected. He gave no
indication he was considering early retirement or a power-sharing
arrangement with de Klerk.
   De Klerk and three senior party leaders emerged tight-lipped from
talks with Botha on Thursday. The talks were ``incisive'' and will
resume at a later date, de Klerk said.
   ``The Crisis Continues,'' said the front-page headline the next
day in Beeld, a pro-government daily.
   De Klerk briefed members of the National Party caucus about the
talks with Botha. Although sworn to secrecy, several legislators
were quoted anonymously in the press as saying there was almost
unanimous support in the caucus for de Klerk and widespread anger at
Botha's perceived intransigence.
   South African political correspondents reported many caucus
members blamed Botha's attitude on misleading information provided
by his inner circle of advisers during his recuperation. Because of
this misinformation, several reports said, Botha underestimated the
depth of caucus support for de Klerk and overestimated its loyalty
to the president.
   In the aftermath of the de Klerk-Botha meeting, there was
sympathy for the president among party officials, wrote Business Day
political reporter Mike Robertson, ``because, having been sheltered
by his personal staff, it was probably the first time he had been
confronted with the reality that virtually the entire caucus wanted
his reign to end.''
   But there is no evidence any such sympathy translates into active
backing. There have been appeals for Botha to be allowed to step
down with dignity, but there have been virtually no calls for de
Klerk to pull back and leave Botha in total command.
   There also are doubts about the president's health. Botha
indicated in his statement Thursday doctors feel he is ready to
resume work. But his left arm was trembling markedly during his only
post-stroke public appearance last month, and his daughter, Rozanne,
was quoted Friday as saying she was ``extremely worried'' about her
father's condition.
   De Klerk, 52, is widely viewed as more pragmatic and open-minded
than Botha, although he is not expected to push through radical
political changes. Many South Africans are seeking the transfer of
power in hopes it will change the mood in the country, with de
Klerk's relatively conciliatory approach replacing the sometimes
bullying demeanor of Botha.
   De Klerk's brother, Willem de Klerk, a former newspaper editor
who broke with the government because of his opposition to South
Africa's system of racial segregation, recently wrote a magazine
article assessing a possible de Klerk presidency.
   ``As a good negotiator, he is certain, within the system, to
defuse some of the tension that has accumulated under the Botha
regime,'' he wrote of his brother. ``He is by nature a democrat. .
.. He is fair, friendly and humble.''
   By contrast, the Johannesburg financial newspaper Business Day,
in an editorial Thursday, said Botha's imperious style had set the
stage for his current plight.
   ``Since his elevation to the presidency, he and his royal family
have been strutting and posturing like hereditary monarchs, holding
ridicule at bay only by the fear that he inspired,'' the editorial
said. ``The fawning around his feet was pitiful to see.''
</TEXT>
