<HEAD>A Look at Major Results of `The Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses-Impact, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie's new novel, ``The Satanic Verses,''
has cast a shadow over the foreign policies of many nations. Here,
at a glance, are some of the major repercussions of the novel:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   IRAN _ Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini orders Rushdie put to death,
and clerics offer a $5.2 million bounty. The government severs ties
with Britain, and an Iranian newspaper says the cut will have a
negative impact on British hostages in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BRITAIN _ Rushdie remains in hiding following Khomeini's Feb. 14
death order. The government announces expulsions of up to 30
Iranians following the severing of diplomatic ties and advises
Britons to leave Lebanon. A major British oil technology fair in
Tehran is canceled.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EUROPEAN ECONOMIC COMMUNITY _ Britain's 11 EEC partners join the
nation in recalling their ambassadors from Tehran and canceling the
exchange of high-level visits with Iran. Norway, Sweden, Austria and
Canada followed suit.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WEST GERMANY: Iran's biggest trade partner suspends plans to
grant at least $1 billion of export credits to help fund Iranian
postwar reconstruction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOVIET UNION _ Caught between wanting to improve relations with
the West and placating its large Moslem population, Moscow offers to
mediate in the confrontation. Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
visits Tehran and appeals for calm.
   The official news agency Tass says Western indignation at the
death sentence is justified but it believes Khomeini perhaps has the
right on religious grounds to denounce ``a man who has insulted
Islam.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   INDIA and PAKISTAN _ Both nations ban the book. Nineteen people
die in anti-Rushdie riots.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JAPAN _ Iran's second-biggest trading partner cancels a visit to
Iran by its foreign ministery.
   _
   DENMARK _ The government halts negotiations for a $100 million
deal involving Iranian oil and Danish cheese.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FRANCE _ France advises oil companies to reduce imports from Iran.
</TEXT>
