<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Bugging     03-11 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Bugging,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swedish Foreign Minister Claims Phone Tapped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Sten Andersson said
Saturday he believes his telephone has been tapped, and he expressed
fears that phones of other senior officials also have been bugged.
   Speaking in a Swedish radio interview, Andersson answered with a
decisive ``yes'' when asked whether he thought he had been bugged.
He declined to identify suspects, saying he lacked evidence.
   ``I know I've been bugged ... It's very alarming,'' he said.
Efforts to track down the perpetrators have failed, he added.
   Parliament speaker Thage G. Peterson told the radio there is no
proof that phones in the Parliament building have been bugged.
   Other officials of the government Social Democrats have
complained of illegal eavesdropping. Swedish newspapers have
suggested alleged extensive wire tapping was part of an unofficial
investigation last year into the unsolved Feb. 28, 1986,
assassination of Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme.
   Swedish law permits bugging with court approval.
</TEXT>
