<FIRST>r i AM-ComicRelief     03-11 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comic Relief,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Noses Raise Millions For Charity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's love affair with plastic red noses raised
millions of dollars for charity for the second straight year,
organizers said Saturday.
   Millions of Britons donned the clown-like protuberances Friday
and put them on cars, planes, mountaintops, statues and pigtails in
50,000 fund-raising events capped by a seven-hour Red Nose Day
television spectacular.
   One jogger, Sam Freemantle, streaked two miles through a Bristol
shopping center wearing only a red nose.
   Comic Relief, the coalition of comedians and aid groups that
organized the event, said Saturday it expected to raise far more
than the $27 million collected from the first Red Nose Day last year.
   Television viewers had pledged $17.9 million by Saturday morning,
far above the $4.3 million pledged at the same time last year.
   In addition, 6 million shiny red noses were sold at pubs, stores
and charity shops for 86 cents each. Another 2 million larger models
for trucks, taxis and cars went for a $1.72 apiece.
   ``It is unbelievable,'' said a Comic Relief spokesman, commenting
on condition of anonymity. ``People have been offering us cars and
percentages from the sale of their houses.''
   Two-thirds of the money raised will go to Third World projects
and the Save the Children Fund, and the rest to programs in Britain
to help young people and the elderly.
   Benny Watts, 20, from Taunton in Somerset, will remember his
contribution forever: he raised $515 by having two red noses
tattooed on his buttocks, and he dropped his trousers in his local
pub to prove it.
   In Bournemouth, an armed gang wearing red noses burst into a Post
Office and pistol-whipped the postmaster but fled empty-handed.
</TEXT>
