<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Crook     03-11 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Crook,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lord Crook, Former British Delegate To United Nations, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Crook, a former British delegate to the United
Nations and vice president of the U.N. Administrative Tribunal for
nearly 20 years, has died, his attorney said Saturday. He was 88.
   Crook, of Carshalton, who received his title in 1947, had been
ill for 3{ years and died Friday at a nursing home in Purley south
of London, said attorney Martin Smith.
   Born Reginald Douglas Crook on March 2, 1901, he joined the Labor
Party and became a senior civil servant, serving as chairman of the
National Dock Labor Board from 1951 to 1965 and general secretary of
the Ministry of Labor Staff Association for 20 years.
   In 1950, he was a member of the British delegation to the U.N.
General Assembly. The following year he became a member of the U.N.
Administrative Tribunal, which resolves work and wage disputes among
employees in the world body. He served as the tribunal's vice
president from 1952-71.
   He is survived by his son, Douglas, who inherits his title.
   There was no word on services or funeral arrangements.
</TEXT>
