<DOCNO> AP890311-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-EasternOverview Bjt   03-11 0957</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Overview, Bjt,0987</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline's Problems Long-Ingrained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Eastern Airlines saga, a 60-year story of a
carrier that World War I flying ace Eddie Rickenbacker helped make
soar but Apollo 8 astronaut Frank Borman couldn't keep out of a
tailspin, is in Chapter 11.
   An unhappy ending is likely, with management blaming ``suicidal''
unions, who say corporate head Frank Lorenzo wants to kill organized
labor.
   Most clues to the case of who's killing Eastern Airlines point to
murder-suicide.
   At Eastern's headquarters, a towering fountain in tribute to
Rickenbacker today is guarded by double-stacked, razor-sharp
concertina wire while strikers on the other side of a fence topped
with more barbed wire chant: ``Hey, hey; ho, ho, Lorenzo's got to
go!''
   Inside, handfuls of management employees rush through quiet halls
past darkened offices as they struggle to maintain a skeleton
schedule during a crippling strike.
   This is the airline that once boasted of flying more passengers
than any carrier other than the Soviets' Aeroflot, and was the
nation's seventh-largest until nearly all union employees walked out
March 4, leading to Thursday's filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization.
   Although Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo and Eastern
President Phil Bakes say Eastern will be rebuilt, unions will fight
them with their own reorganization plan and continue seeking a
buyout.
   The unions say Eastern is under deadly assault by Lorenzo, who
brought a union-busting reputation to the company three years ago
and a ``take-it-or-lose-your-job'' management style to a company
with some of the industry's strongest-willed unions.
   Massive concessions were demanded; firings, suspensions and
grievances skyrocketed; assets were spun off or sold, mostly to the
benefit of Lorenzo's parent Texas Air; and complex loans and
long-term notes from Eastern made it appear the carrier was helping
subsidize Lorenzo's non-union Continental Airlines.
   Charged with what management calls ``economic suicide'' are the
unions, particularly the pilots. Few were surprised that the
Machinists union's 17-month contract dispute and refusal to make
more concessions ended in strike, but management was stunned when
nearly all 3,600 pilots refused to cross picket lines.
   The pilots union remembered that Lorenzo used pilots to keep
Continental flying during a Machinists strike in 1983, but that the
pilots, too, lost their contracts in bankruptcy reorganization.
   Leading the Machinists is fiery District 100 President Charles E.
Bryan, with a stubborness born of studies of Zen, yoga, Gandhi and
Martin Luther King Jr., and a view of the conflict as that between
good and evil.
   ``Charlie is like one of those birthday candles that you blow out
and it comes back on,'' former company negotiator Jack Johnson once
said.
   Borman recently compared Bryan to cult leader Jim Jones, who led
the 1978 mass suicide in Guyana, and says he has ``a certifiably
insane dream of running the airline himself.''
   Eastern's history has been a long roller-coaster.
   It was born May 1, 1928, as Pitcairn Aviation, a mail carrier
that made its first Miami landing Dec. 1. It began passenger service
in 1930 and was renamed Eastern in 1938.
   The carrier was losing money in 1935 when Rickenbacker climbed
aboard, using his war-hero status and forceful personality to build
Eastern into a giant force in the industry.
   Eastern became the dominant north-south carrier east of the
Mississippi and boomed when post-World War II prosperity brought
leisure time to most Americans.
   National Airlines introduced jets to commercial aviation in 1958,
but Rickenbacker didn't believe they would work for carrying
passengers.
   By the time he left Eastern in 1963, the company was losing money
and had become known for benign neglect of passengers, some of whom
formed the ``We Hate Eastern Airlines'' club.
   Borman became president and chief executive in 1975, after the
company lost a then-staggering $53 million in 1973.
   As with Rickenbacker, Borman capitalized on his hero status and
brought a new style of pride and dedication. In 1976, he persuaded
his unions to accept a wage freeze.
   A 1976 profit led to a five-year Variable Earnings Program _ the
company held 3.5 percent of the workers' earnings, but if profits
were made the workers would get that 3.5 percent back plus an
additional 3.5 percent.
   The first two years brought employees nice Christmas checks, but
then came airline deregulation and stronger competition. Borman
countered by buying more planes, expanding service, going deeper in
debt.
   Bryan became the Machinists leader in 1980 after attacking the
VEP. The company unilaterally extended the program by a year,
leading to a 1983 showdown in which Borman, on the day of a strike
deadline, gave the Machinists 32 percent raises he said Eastern
couldn't afford.
   Borman gave the unions seats on the board of directors and
replaced the VEP with a stock-for-pay program that allowed employees
to acquire 25 percent of Eastern stock.
   By early 1986, Bryan was urging a full employee takeover.
Management fought back by demanding concessions. The pilots and
flight attendants agreed to 20 percent cuts.
   Bryan refused to make concessions unless Borman left. The board
refused to allow Bryan to dictate to it and sold out to Lorenzo on
Feb. 23, 1986.
   The next day, Lorenzo said: ``There ain't no Santa Claus.''
   Employees lost voting shares in the transaction and their seats
on the board.
   Lorenzo's management called for nearly 30 percent in cuts from
unions that had been giving back wages for much of the past 10
years. It made no bones about its plans _ if Eastern couldn't be
fixed the way management wanted, it would be tanked.
   The unions decided to take their chances.
   ``So here we are,'' reflected James Ashlock, an Eastern spokesman
or lobbyist for 22 years. ``At least now maybe we have a chance to
rebuild it right.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
