<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-USBishops-Glance     03-11 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-US Bishops-Glance,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Positions of Vatican and U.S. Catholic Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Vatican-US Bishops, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following is a summary of positions taken
by the U.S. Roman Catholic hierarchy and Vatican officials on some
issues discussed during a meeting with Pope John Paul II. Cardinal
Joseph Bernardin of Chicago provided the summary.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feminism _ The Vatican raised questions about ``ideological
feminism'' and its dangers to the Catholic Church. U.S. bishops
called for a ``sound philosophical theological critique'' of radical
feminism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Non-sexist language _ Vatican and U.S. Catholic leaders agreed it
can and should be incorporated into the liturgy as long as it does
not impinge on scriptural and doctrinal matters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Altar girls _ Some Americans spoke up in favor of altar girls. It
was noted a special Vatican commission is studying the issue, but a
ban remains in effect. Some U.S. dioceses nonetheless permit the
practice.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Traditionalists _ Some U.S. bishops expressed concern that some
traditionalists seek to undermine the authority of local bishops.
The Vatican said exceptions can be granted to allow the Latin
Tridentine Mass, provided it is not aimed at promoting dissension.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Annulments _ A Vatican official expressed concern about the
number of annulments in the United States. U.S. bishops defended
their church marriage tribunals, saying they follow the norms and
procedures of church law and would welcome a review by Rome.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Catholic universities _ U.S. bishops said a papal document in
preparation on higher education should be sensitive to the concerns
of college administrators on such issues as Catholic identity and
academic freedom.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Priestly celibacy _ The U.S. bishops said there is a need to
develop ``a rationale for celibacy which will be more credible and
appealing in our times for both priests and laity.''
</TEXT>
