<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Crash     03-11 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Crash,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Americans Killed in Crash of Tourist Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane carrying American tourists back
from a sightseeing trip crashed into a construction site on a
college campus, narrowly missing crowded classrooms but killing all
10 people aboard, officials said Saturday.
   Officials at Lima's airport said the pilot of the plane radioed
the control tower that he was having problems shortly before
Friday's crash in the capital's San Miguel neighborhood.
   ``It was flying as if it were a truck without brakes. It sounded
as if the motors were turned off,'' said Jesus Tarazona. Tarazona
was on the roof of his two-story home when the plane slashed through
thick fog shortly before nightfall and smashed into a two-story
building under construction at the University of San Martin de
Porras.
   A building next to the construction site was filled with about
150 students attending classes.
   The U.S. Embassy identified the American victims as John Howe,
81, and his wife Barbara, 72, of Hagerstown, Md.; Robert Fisher, 66,
and his wife Ruth, 62, of Moorestown, N.J.; Dorothy Menzies, 77, and
her daughter, Virginia Fennel, 48, of Hickory, N.C.; and Virginia
Hall, 78, and her granddaughter, Mary Shuford, 28, also of Hickory,
N.C.
   The Aerocondor flight's pilot and copilot, both Peruvians, also
were killed.
   Johan Leuridan, a university dean who was visiting the work site,
was hit by falling bricks and hospitalized with a back injury.
Police said all the workers at the site had left 15 minutes before
the crash.
   Hugo Monzon, general manager of Aerocondor, a small airline that
provides air taxi service to small towns in Peru, said the plane was
a British-made Norman Islander purchased six years ago.
   He said the cause of the accident had not been determined.
   The plane crashed nearly four miles from the Lima airport.
   Some students in the classroom building near the crash site told
reporters the sound from the crash was so loud they thought a
terrorist bomb had gone off or their building was collapsing.
   The plane smashed into a wall on the second floor of the
partially constructed building. A wing landed on the floor, and part
of the fuselage tumbled into a garden below.
   Several residents of the San Miguel district said they heard the
plane's engines sputtering seconds before the crash. But they said
they were unable to see the aircraft because of heavy fog.
   An Aerocondor official said the plane was returning to Lima after
having flown over the famous Nazca lines 250 miles southeast of the
capital.
   The Nazca lines are giant pre-Columbian drawings on the desert
believed to represent a primitive calendar used for calculating
planting and harvesting seasons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
