<DOCNO> AP890311-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 1514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Sikhs     03-11 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Sikhs,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militants Kill 12 In Upsurge Of Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants in the northwestern state
of Punjab killed at least 12 people, including a politician who had
survived two earlier assassination attempts, news reports said
Saturday.
   Suraj Prakash Malhotra, a local leader of Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi's Congress Party, and Gajjan Singh, a state leader of the
Communist Party of India, were among the victims in a series of
attacks, Press Trust of India said.
   Militants have waged a bloody insurgency for an independent Sikh
nation since 1982, claiming they are discriminated against by the
country's Hindu majority.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's population but are a majority
in Punjab state.
   Malhotra, a former town president, was slain by militants Friday
night in his house in Ropar, the United News of India said. Malhotra
had survived two earlier attempts on his life, UNI said.
   Ropar is 155 miles north of New Delhi.
   Singh was gunned down by Sikh militants Saturday in the village
of Kalake near Amritsar, PTI said. Amritsar is about 280 miles
northwest of New Delhi.
   UNI said militants also shot to death a man outside the Golden
Temple in Amritsar. Another victim was dragged from his house in
Chak Sikander village and killed, and two neighbors were slain when
they tried to help him, the news agency said.
   Police said at least six others had been killed in separate
incidents across the state in the past 24 hours, PTI said.
   At least 2,400 people were killed by Sikh militants last year,
more than double the number killed in 1987.
   More than 380 people have been killed so far this year.
</TEXT>
