<FIRST>r a AM-People-O'Neal-Fawcett     03-11 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-O'Neal-Fawcett,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ryan and Farrah Say They'll Marry _ Someday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Longtime companions Ryan O'Neal and Farrah
Fawcett tried tying the knot once _ but they ran out of gas.
   They say a second attempt is forthcoming, but the actors aren't
sure when.
   ``We were headed for the church but ran out of gas,'' Miss
Fawcett says of an attempt to wed during a vacation three years ago.
``It was a blizzard and no one would stop for us. It took hours to
get back to a warm place and, by that time, we were no longer in the
wedding mood.''
   The couple met 10 years ago while Miss Fawcett was wife of the
``Six Million Dollar Man,'' actor Lee Majors.
   ``Lee asked if I played racquetball, which I never did. I
reluctantly agreed to come over to the house and Farrah cooked
dinner. She had trouble getting rid of me from then on,'' O'Neal
says in an interview published in the current issue of USA Weekend.
   O'Neal, 47, and Miss Fawcett, 42, have a 4-year-old son, Redmond.
   ``We will definitely get married. We just haven't found the right
time. I feel married now,'' Miss Fawcett said.
   O'Neal's latest film, ``Chances Are,'' which he calls ``a kind,
decent picture,'' is now opening around the country. But, he says,
he doesn't work much anymore.
   ``Mostly I'm offered Rambo ripoffs. I'm pretty much semi-retired.
I don't want to be in any more bad pictures, so I'm not in a hurry
anymore,'' he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
