<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Fire     03-11 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Fire,0195</SECOND>
<UNK>Fire Ravages Hillside Slum Leaving More Than 500 Families Homeless</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire swept through a hillside
slum area in northern Rio de Janeiro on Saturday and left 500 people
homeless, but no one was injured, officials said.
   The fire started at around 5:00 a.m. in a home in the Parque
Alegria hillside community, fire chief Lt. Silvio Souza said.
   Souza said the flames raced through more than 150 fragile wood
and brick huts that sit atop the hills overlooking Rio's north zone.
   Firefighters, struggling to get trucks and water hoses up the
rugged hill, battled the fire for three hours in a confused scene of
smoke, screams and fire engine and ambulance sirens.
   Residents threw buckets of water on the flames and rushed madly
about with refrigerators, stoves, and cabinets on their shoulders
and backs to save them from the flames, the fire chief said.
   Miraculously, Souza said, no one was hurt.
   ``The whole area was completely destroyed,'' the fire chief said.
``Only some hollow huts made of brick were left standing.'' He said
the cause of the fire was not known.
