<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     03-11 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Government Orders Beirut Airport Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian Cabinet ordered Beirut's
airport closed Saturday after Druse militiamen shelled the city's
port and the Defense Ministry compound. Police said at least six
people died in the latest violence.
   As thunderous explosions echoed around the city, the Cabinet
headed by army commander Gen. Michel Aoun ordered the closure
because of ``threats to civil aviation safety.''
   But Moslem officials running the airport on Beirut's southern
edge said they would not comply.
   One official, Rida Fawli, said the airport _ Lebanon's only civil
aviation facility _ ``will remain open and functioning.''
   The fighting underscored heightening tensions over an air-and-sea
blockade enforced by Aoun since Monday. The blockade is aimed at
illegal ports operated by the country's warring militias.
   Police said at least six people were killed and 32 wounded in
four days of fighting, the worst across Beirut's dividing Green Line
and hills overlooking the capital in the past two years.
   Clashes erupted Wednesday around the mountaintop town of Souk
El-Gharb, where Aoun's predominantly Christian units have fought
with artillery and tank cannon almost daily against militiamen of
Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party.
   According to police count, four civilians have been killed and 15
others wounded in the fighting around Souk El-Gharb, 15 miles
southeast of Beirut.
   The deserted summer resort town, whose population of 15,000 fled
early on in the 14-year-old civil war, is in a strategic network of
mountain roads leading to the Christian heartland northeast of
Beirut.
   On Friday evening, Aoun's forces battled Syrian-backed Moslem
militiamen in the abandoned commercial district straddling Beirut's
shell-ravaged official harbor.
   On Saturday night, Druse gunners perched on Lebanon's central
mountain range around Souk El-Gharb shelled the port, the Defense
Ministry housing Aoun's command in suburban Yarze and the nearby
officers' residence complex in Jamhour, police said.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said at least two people were killed and 17 wounded in
the shelling in Jamhour.
   The spokesman said there were no casualties or damage reported at
the Defense Ministry, about five miles northeast of Beirut.
   The artillery duels later spread to 21 Moslem and Christian
residential districts around Beirut, and thousands of residents
sought refuge in basements and bomb shelters, police said.
   ``In view of worsening security conditions that pose a threat to
the safety of civil aviation and passengers at Beirut international
airport ... the government orders the airport closed until further
notice,'' Aoun's public works minister, Maj. Gen. Edgar Malouf, said
in a statement.
   But a statement issued by Jumblatt's office at the airport said:
``Nothing could happen as long as the Syrian army controls and
protects the airport. It shall continue functioning without
interruption.''
   Jumblatt serves as public works and tourism minister in the
Moslem cabinet of acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
   Hoss' cabinet and Aoun's Christian administration have been
embroiled in a power struggle since Sept. 22.
   Jumblatt is allied with Syria, which maintains 40,000 troops in
northern and eastern Lebanon and in western and southern Beirut
under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   The two Cabinets emerged when President Amin Gemayel's six-year
term in office expired and Parliament was unable to elect a
successor.
   Minutes before he stepped down, Gemayel named Aoun prime minister
of an interim military Cabinet.
   Moslems and leftists rejected his appointment and pledged
allegiance to Hoss.
</TEXT>
