<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0539 03-11 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0539,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Uprising Cost Israel $666 Million In 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with report schools reopening.
Pickup 7th pvs, ``Defense Minister ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestinian uprising cost Israel $666
million in 1988 and nearly wiped out its economic growth, and it may
exact a similar toll this year, a Cabinet minister was quoted
Saturday as saying.
   Gad Yaacobi blamed the losses on higher military spending,
reduced production, and lost tourism and foreign investment.
Yaacobi, of the left-leaning Labor Party, was economics minister
until November, when he became communications minister.
   Arab reports said four Palestinians were wounded in clashes with
troops Saturday. The army confirmed two injuries.
   Israel radio quoted Yaacobi as saying Israel's $35 billion
economy grew 1 percent last year, instead of a forecasted 2.5
percent. In 1987, it grew 5 percent.
   At the same time, the value of goods and services in the occupied
lands shrunk from $1.5 billion in 1987 to $1.2 billion, according to
Palestinian economist Samir Abdullah.
   Also Saturday, Israel television reported authorities plan
gradually to reopen the 1,200 West Bank schools, shut for most of
the 15-month uprising.
   Olivier Rafowicz, spokesman for the military government, said
they would decide later this week. ``We want to reopen the schools,
but we want to be sure this is not accompanied by violence,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, meanwhile, said Palestinian
leaders have expressed support for his proposal to hold elections in
the occupied territories to choose a delegation for direct peace
talks with Israel.
   ``I have received hints that the approach I proposed appeals to
not just a small number of the leading figures among the residents
of the (occupied) territories,'' Rabin said in an interview Israel
radio broadcast Saturday.
   His remarks came after leading Palestinians rejected the plan,
saying the Palestine Liberation Organization is their sole
representative and elections only can be held after Israel withdraws.
   ``The people here will not elect a leadership to be in
competition with the PLO,'' Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij, a political
moderate, said Saturday. ``It will only drive a wedge between us and
our brothers on the outside.''
   Four Palestinians, including a 12-year-old boy, were shot and
wounded in Saturday clashes with Israeli troops in the Gaza Strip,
Arab hospital officials said. The army confirmed two wounded.
   Since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987, 394 Palestinians have been
killed. Seventeen Israelis have died.
   Rabin outlined a troop redeployment plan to ``reduce the burden''
of reserve soldiers by cutting their duties from a maximum of 62
days a year to 44 days.
   ``In Gaza and the West Bank, regular forces and fewer reserve
troops will serve in areas known as trouble spots,'' Rabin said. In
addition, specially trained border police units will take over some
areas.
   The radio interview was broadcast a day after the army shifted
some troops out of Gaza Strip refugee camps. It marks a shift in
government policy from emphasizing a widespread army presence to
using fewer, but better-trained anti-riot units.
   The redeployment also came as Foreign Minister Moshe Arens left
for a 10-day visit to the United States, where he is expected to
encounter pressure to reduce friction in the occupied lands.
   Rabin denied troops were redeployed to appease the United States.
``There is no connection to whether the Americans want this or
not,'' he said.
</TEXT>
