<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArmsTalks     03-11 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yazov Says Vienna Talks Can Spur Strategic Weapons Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister was quoted as saying Saturday
that new East-West talks on cutting conventional weapons and
increasing European security should spur reductions in strategic and
chemical weapons.
   ``We hope that the beginning of the Vienna negotiations will
boost the general disarmament process, specifically negotiations on
50 percent cuts in Soviet and U.S. strategic weapons and on a
convention to ban and eliminate chemical weapons,'' the official
Tass news agency quoted Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov as saying
in an interview.
   ``This process should also involve tactical nuclear weapons and
naval forces, and confidence- and security-building measures should
be extended not only to ground troops but also to the navies and
independent air force activities,'' he told Tass.
   The Vienna talks between the 16 nations of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization and the seven countries of the Warsaw Pact began
Thursday.
   Warsaw Pact states proposed a reduction of 10 percent to 15
percent below the lowest level of arms held by either side in the
first phase of conventional arms reductions. Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze has insisted the talks also cover aircraft,
an area in which the Soviets contend the West has an advantage.
   The Western alliance called for extensive cuts in East bloc
battle tanks, artillery, and armored troop carriers, which it
considers the key forces that could be used for an invasion or
surprise attack on Western Europe.
   NATO has offered to make smaller cuts in those categories.
   The United States and the Soviet Union agreed in 1987 to
eliminate their medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles, but
subsequent talks bogged down on a proposed cut in strategic weapons.
   The Soviet Union has said it is eager for progress in that field,
but understands the administration of President Bush will need time
to put together a negotiating position.
   Yazov said parallel Vienna talks on conventional weapons and
better monitoring facilities to build confidence in Europe ``offer
the possibility of moving toward durable security in Europe on a
larger scale, combining limitations of and reductions in armed
forces and armaments with more openness with regard to military
activities under strict control.''
   Both sides in the conventional arms talks have called for tough
verification measures to ensure the opponent is not cheating.
</TEXT>
