<FIRST>r a AM-CowpensLaunch     03-11 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cowpens Launch,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Cruiser Cowpens Launched At Bath Iron Works</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATH, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's new guided-missile cruiser Cowpens
was launched Saturday at the Bath Iron Works.
   The cruiser, the latest in the Ticonderoga class, is named after
the Revolutionary War battle that was fought on Jan. 17, 1781, near
Cowpens, S.C. It is the second Navy ship to bear the name.
   Navy Secretary William L. Ball Jr., a South Carolina native,
praised the launching as the latest in ``an unbroken series of
successes'' in the service's Aegis cruiser program.
   The Cowpens, he said, ``represents revitalization of the Navy and
the restoration of national pride.''
   A delegation of congressional representatives from South Carolina
also attended the launching.
   The cruiser Cowpens is 567 feet long, 55 feet wide and displaces
about 9,600 tons. Considered the most sophisticated air-defense ship
in the world, the cruiser will carry a unique wrap-around radar
system that allows it to ``see'' in all directions at once.
   The Cowpens is the fifth Aegis cruiser to be launched by the Bath
Iron Works, and is to join the Monterey and Normandy at the
shipyard's outfitting piers.
   A crowd estimated at about 3,000 attended the launching along the
blustery banks of the Kennebec River.
</TEXT>
