<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-AfghanDecision     03-11 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Afghan Decision,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Moscow Party Boss Identifies Four Who Decided on Afghan Invasion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A maverick Communist leader said Saturday that just
four men decided to send troops into Afghanistan _ President Leonid
Brezhnev, Defense Minister Dmitri Ustinov, Foreign Minister Andrei
Gromyko and Politburo ideologist Michael Suslov.
   It has long been reported that only a handful of members of the
ruling Politburo were involved in the fateful decision that sent
15,000 Soviet soldiers to their deaths in Afghanistan.
   But Boris Yeltsin, a former candidate member of the Politburo who
was demoted from Moscow Communist Party chief after criticizing the
leadership, was the first official to name the individuals.
   Yeltsin's revelation came in a speech Saturday before 800 people
at the Kuntsevo Theater, where he was campaigning for the new
Congress of People's Deputies. He did not give his source, but he
likely would have been one of the first let in on the secret. He
remains one of the 300-odd members of the Communist Party's
policy-making Central Committee.
   Other members of the Central Committee said last year they did
not know who was responsible. But the subject suddenly was opened to
discussion in February when the Soviet troops left Afghanistan after
nine years of war.
   The four men Yeltsin identified were all top Kremlin power
brokers in 1979, and likely candidates for a coterie close-knit and
powerful enough to make such a drastic decision.
   Brezhnev, then 73, held the top positions in both the government
and the Communist Party _ president and party general secretary.
Gromyko, then 70, had ruled the Foreign Ministry for 22 years.
   Gen. Ustinov, then 71, was both minister of defense and marshal
of the army. And Suslov, then 77, was the Politburo member in charge
of ideology who took on a number of Brezhnev's duties in 1979.
   Gromyko retired from the presidency and the Politburo last
autumn; Brezhnev and Suslov died in 1982 and Ustinov died in 1984.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda raised official doubts about the
wisdom of intervening in Afghanistan in a front-page article Feb.
15, the day the last Soviet soldier came home.
   ``It is possible to doubt the Brezhnev leadership's evaluation of
the level of military threat,'' Pravda said. ``Such vitally
important decisions as the use of troops cannot be decided secretly
by a small circle of people, without the sanction of the
Parliament.''
   Yeltsin said Saturday that Brezhnev, Gromyko, Ustinov, and Suslov
made the fateful decision ``and then told the Politburo.''
   The Politburo is the ruling body in the Soviet Communist Party's
oligarchy, and its members, then 14, would have been expected to
take such an important step as a group.
   ``If the people had decided, there would have been a different
decision,'' Yeltsin said in explaining his campaign call for a
referendum law in the Soviet Union. Instead, 15,000 Soviet soldiers
died and, in the end, the Soviet Union didn't win the war, he said.
   Yeltsin was ousted as Moscow Communist Party leader in 1987 after
his harsh attacks on corruption angered too many people. He is now
first deputy chairman of the State Construction Committee.
   Yeltsin is running against the director of a Moscow auto factory
in the first multi-candidate national elections in Soviet history.
He called for more rapid economic reform and cancellation of all
privileges enjoyed by the elite, particularly access to hard-to-find
goods and services.
   ``If we lack something, then workers, government ministers and
the general secretary should lack the same things.'' he said to loud
applause.
</TEXT>
