<HEAD>Suburban Washington Resident Claims $3 Million `Lotto America' Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second time this year, a Washington
D.C.-area resident has claimed a ``Lotto America'' jackpot prize,
district lottery officials said Saturday.
   ``Lightning can strike the same place twice,'' said Lorraine A.
Green, district lottery executive director.
   Conrad Yanguba, 40, a computer operator from Prince George's
County, Md., won $3 million in the March 4 drawing in the Des
Moines, Iowa-based lottery.
   Yanguba did not attend Saturday's press conference because of
``family commitments,'' lottery officials said. His winning numbers
were 3-9-24-33-37-49. Yanguba will receive 20 annual payments of
$150,000 before state and federal taxes.
   He is the second area lottery player to win at Lotto America
since the game began in February 1988. The first winner, Lee Nelson
of Alexandria, Va., won $16 million in the Feb. 18 drawing.
