<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-11 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Near Tahoe, Mostly warm Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell Saturday on the high country of the Nevada-California
border, while warm weather elsewhere melted snow and caused local
flooding.
   Wind gusted to 70 mph south of Reno, Nev., during the morning as
a result of a strong cold front which left 6 inches of snow
overnight at higher elevations of the Tahoe Valley along the
Nevada-California border, and about 2 inches of snow at lower levels
near Lake Tahoe.
   Unseasonably warm temperatures elsewhere melted snow cover and
there was flooding on the Big Muddy River at Murphysboro, Ill., the
National Weather Service said.
   Melting snow also added to problems at Hooper, Neb., where an ice
jam caused local flooding.
   Other streams for which warnings were posted include the
Pecatonica River in southwestern Wisconsin; the Weiser River near
Weiser, Idaho; the John Day River at Service Creek, Ore.; and the
Umitilla River at Pendleton, Ore.
   Elsewhere, light rain was scattered over North Dakota at noon,
and showers were widely scattered over the northern coast of
California. Rain and freezing rain extended over northern and
western Montana.
   Afternoon temperatures were much warmer than normal for mid-March
over much of the Plains, and from Arizona across southeastern Idaho.
   Record highs for the date included 89 at Amarillo, Texas; 71 at
Cheyenne, Wyo.; 87 at Lubbock, Texas; and 82 at Pueblo, Colo.
   Temperatures only hit the upper 50s in Michigan but people took
advantage of the break, with more than 500 golfers turning out by
noon at the Maple Lane Golf Course in Sterling Heights, said golf
pro Linc Jackson.
   ``It's more like a Saturday in early May,'' Detroit Zoo cashier
Gwen Lanier said of attendance.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 21
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 92 at Childress, Texas. Saturday's
low for the Lower 48 states was 4 degrees below zero at Houlton,
Maine.
   For Sunday, scattered snow showers were forecast over northern
New England and northeastern New York state. Showers were forecast
along the northern Pacific Coast, and over northwestern Montana.
   Highs in the 20s were predicted over northern Maine, Upper
Michigan and northeastern Minnesota; in the 30s and 40s from the
remainder of New England across the remainder of the Great Lakes,
the upper Mississippi Valley, North Dakota, the northeastern half of
South Dakota and northeastern Montana; in the 50s and 60s from New
Jersey and the remainder of New York state across North Carolina,
the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, the middle Mississippi
Valley, the central Plains, the remainder of South Dakota, the
Rockies, the Great Basin, the northern Plateau and the northern
two-thirds of the Pacific Coast; in the 90s over north-central
through central Texas, and from southwestern Texas across southern
Arizona; and generally in the 70s and 80s elsewhere around the
nation.
</TEXT>
