<DOCNO> AP890311-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 1807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     03-11 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Hopes To Reach Agreement On Relief Supplies To Sudanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUGLAD, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atan Maywin stood under the harsh sun in
front of her makeshift hut Saturday describing how her six children
died from starvation and disease as they fled the civil war in
southern Sudan.
   She arrived in this town, 460 miles southwest of the capital of
Khartom, on Thursday _ one of about 300 refugees who enter Muglad
daily seeking safety and food.
   Hundreds of thousands of refugees have fled battle areas and an
international relief program under United Nations auspices hopes to
transport 170,000 tons of food and supplies to distribution points
before the rainy season starts in May.
   But there has been no agreement between relief organizers and
leaders of the rebels' Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) on
shipments of the supplies. In previous years SPLA forces have fired
at planes and trucks carrying relief supplies, saying the army was
using them to transport equipment to its troops.
   There are some 2.25 million people in southern Sudan. Last year
it is estimated that as many as 500,000 perished from war-related
causes, with many starving in isolated villages.
   James Grant, executive director of the U.N. Children's Fund
(UNICEF) returned to Khartoum Saturday after a day of talks with
SPLA leaders in the Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa.
   Grant said Gen. Lon Akol, the SPLA's second in command, asked for
time to study a proposed ``month of tranquility,'' which would
virtually amount to a cease-fire, to move relief supplies into
position.
   Grant spoke with reporters after meeting Prime Minister Sadek
Mahdi and informing him about the talks with the rebels. Mahdi's
government has accepted the relief plan.
   ``The SPLA took a strong position that there was a need for food
and that they would work to get it to their people,'' Grant said.
``We have yet to receive a formal reply.
   We are going to work with the assumption that we will get
agreement, if not on a month of tranquility, then at the very least
on bubbles of tranquility for the eight points in the plan,'' he
said.
   The eight points involve transporting aid by airlifts and truck,
train and barge convoys to both government- and rebel-held areas.
   In Addis Ababa an SPLA official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said no agreement had been reached on a cease-fire to
allow relief shipments into the south.
   The official commented on the meeting with Grant, Julia Taft,
head of the U.S. office of Foreign Disasters Assistance, and
representatives of Western donor agencies.
   ``We discussed with them recent developments in Sudan, but we did
not reach any conclusive agreement,'' the official said. The SPLA
has its headquarters in Addis Ababa.
   U.N. officials have estimated that 100,000 people might perish if
the ``month of tranquility'' operation cannot be carried out. Other
officials have said the death toll could exceed 600,000.
   The Sudanese government is dominated by Moslems and has imposed
Islamic law, while many people in the south are Christians and
animists. The SPLA took up arms against the government in 1985,
demanding autonomy and a larger share for the south of Sudan's
wealth and development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
