<FIRST>r i AM-PlanesDown     03-11 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Planes Down,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Object Spotted In Ocean Search For Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers searching Saturday for the
Minnesota pilot of a small plane that plunged into the Atlantic
Ocean spotted a bright orange object that appeared to be a life
jacket.
   A search for another American whose small plane also crashed into
the Atlantic was called off.
   Todd Michaelson, 29, of Minneapolis, ditched his Piper Saratoga
into the sea about 990 miles northeast of St. John's, Newfoundland
on Wednesday after reporting engine trouble while flying to Ireland.
   A flare thought to have been fired by Michaelson, who had a
survival suit and life raft, was spotted late Wednesday night and a
seat cushion was seen Thursday.
   Rescue officials said they continued that search because of the
flare sighting.
   Rescue aircraft and commercial vessels on Friday halted the
search for a Cessna 210 that ditched in the same area 12 hours after
Michaelson's plane went down.
   Its pilot, an American in his 40s, has not been identified. His
plane also reported engine trouble while en route to Ireland.
   Capt. Patrick Phelan of the Halifax search and rescue center said
the American pilot was presumed dead. A spokesman for his employer,
Tim McCandless Inc. of Waterloo, Iowa, said the Cessna left Gander,
Newfoundland.
   ``We've determined that the possibility for survival is next to
nil right now due to the conditions during the ditch and the
temperatures and the extensive search area coverage with no
indication right now,'' said Capt. Patrick Phelan of the Halifax
Search and Rescue center.
   A U.S. Coast Guard plane and a Soviet weather ship joined a
Canadian vessel in Saturday's search for Michaelson.
