<SECOND>AM-Panama-Oil Spill,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Spill At Entrance To Panama Canal After Ships Collide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker and a cargo ship collided
near the Pacific Ocean entrance of the Panama Canal and an estimated
200 tons of combustible oil spilled into coastal waters, an offical
reported Saturday.
   Jose Reyes, operations director for the National Port Authority,
told The Associated Press that port authority workers and members of
the Panamanian Defense Forces were working to clean up the spill and
to direct the oil out to sea.
   He said the accident occurred Friday when the Ecuadorean cargo
ship Isla Santay, 528 feet long and 75 feet wide, collided with the
599-foot-long, 105-foot-wide British petroleum tanker Probobravo
near Panama Bay.
   One of the Probobravo's oil tanks was ripped open, Reyes said.
   He said he did not know if the spill had damaged marine and plant
life but the collision had not affected traffic in the 50-mile-long
waterway. An average of some 33 ships pass through the canal daily.
