<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-11 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright And Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's in a name? Well, that depends on
whether you consider yourself Michigander, a Michiganite, a
Michiganian _ or maybe even a bit Michiganer.
   Abraham Lincoln is said to have coined ``Michigander'' in 1848 in
a sarcastic speech. State archivists have found one 1800s reference
to ``Michiganite.'' An 1871 pamphlet referred to ``Michiganer.''
   The Associated Press in Michigan uses ``Michiganian.'' The
Detroit Free Press _ after some energetic writers conducted a poll _
endorsed ``Michigander'' and included it in its stylebook for
writers.
   State government skirts the issue. Roger Peters of the
Legislative Service Bureau said drafting experts have no policy and
tend to avoid the matter.
   In 1981, the state House debated the matter, defeating
Michigander 51-42 and selecting Michiganian for official use. But
the Senate never passed the measure.
   The only official reference experts could uncover was a 1980 law
creating a state commission to serve the aging. It included the
title: ``This act shall be known and may be cited as the older
Michiganian Act.''
   That _ absent a counterattack from 'gander backers _ apparently
has carried the day.
   ``Technically, I think Michiganian is preferred,'' said David
Anderson, professor of American thought and language at Michigan
State University. ``You're not from Michigand, you're from Michigan.
Michigander adds something that doesn't belong.''
   But, he added: ``It's not one of the pressing problems Michigan
has to solve.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Detroit-area arena has a sympathetic
ear for those parents who take their children to rock concerts and
can't stand the high decibels of heavy metal music.
   The Palace, home of the Detroit Pistons basketball team,
introduced the ``Quiet Room,'' at a March 4 concert featuring the
heavy metal band Poison, said Patrick O'Connor, a spokesman for the
stadium. About 125 parents used it.
   ``We actually got a lot of calls from parents saying they were
concerned about letting their kids go to the show,'' he said. ``The
Quiet Room is a way to alleviate those concerns.''
   In the Quiet Room, parents can peacefully kill time while their
kids enjoy the show, O'Connor said. It solves the problems involved
with dropping off the children and returning to pick them up, he
said.
   Parents need not buy a ticket to use the quiet room _ actually a
banquet room. They can read, watch television, or even catch the
concert on the in-house closed-circuit monitors, he said.
   After the concert, parents catch up with offspring at a
designated meeting place, O'Connor said.
   Marilyn Desjardins, another Palace spokeswoman, said the Quiet
Room concept was adapted from a similar program at the Capital
Centre in Landover, Md. Other arenas nationwide also have quiet
rooms, she said.
</TEXT>
