<FIRST>r a AM-LeavenworthEscapee     03-11 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leavenworth Escapee,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Escapes From U.S. Penitentiary; First In 12 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEAVENWORTH, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted bank robber used a disguise
to walk out the front door of the U.S. Penitentiary, the first
prisoner in 12 years to escape from the maximum security prison.
   Robert Allen Litchfield, 40, who was serving 140 years for armed
robbery and a previous escape, was reported missing after the 4 p.m.
count Friday at the maximum security prison.
   Kent Pekarek of the U.S. Marshal's office would not say how
Litchfield was dressed, and officials at the prison refused to say
how the prisoner was allowed to walk out.
   Pekarek said Litchfield had arranged to have a taxi waiting at
the prison and was driven to a bank in Leavenworth. He went into the
bank and brought out a package.
   He then told the taxi driver that he was a safety inspector from
Washington, D.C., and needed to have the package delivered to Kansas
City International Airport.
   The cab driver took the package to the airport as instructed, but
found no one waiting to pick it up. ``That was just to throw us off,
to make us think he went to the airport,'' Pekarek said.
   Litchfield walked to a grocery store and dropped off his disguise
in a dumpster, Pekarek said. He then walked to a restaurant and met
an accomplice, who gave him $5,000 in $100 bills.
   Pekarek said officials know the identity of the accomplice, but
didn't say how they knew the precise amount of the currency.
   After getting the money, Pekarek said, Litchfield flagged down
another cab and asked the driver to take him to a place near Bonner
Springs, about 20 miles south of Leavenworth, where he said his
wife's car had broken down.
   During that ride, Litchfield reportedly changed his instructions
and told the driver to take him to an appliance store at the Indian
Springs Shopping Center in Kansas City, Kan.
   The driver dropped him off at the store at 4:30 p.m., and
authorities are picking up the trail at that point, Pekarek said.
   ``We have additional sources and are receiving more information
about his activities, which we expect to lead to his arrest,'' the
marshal said.
   Litchfield used a similar method to escape from the Federal
Correctional Institution in Talladega, Ala., two years ago, Pekarek
said.
   Dan McCauley, a prison spokesman, said Litchfield was serving
time for bank robbery and use of a firearm in Florida and Georgia,
and for prison escape. His last known address before being sent to
prison was Boca Raton, Fla.
   Pekarek said Litchfield is considered armed and dangerous.
</TEXT>
