<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Crash 4thLd-Writethru a0588 03-11 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Crash, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0588,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Continues for Bodies of 22 Missing From Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 10 bodies recovered. Pickup
7th graf `Purses, one...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos DDN2, NY50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DRYDEN, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Work crews using snowmobiles and snowplows
recovered bodies from a woods and looked for clues Saturday to the
cause of an Air Ontario jet crash in central Canada that killed 24
people.
   Officials on Saturday found the voice and flight data recorders,
or black boxes. While they were badly burned in Friday's crash, they
could still be used, said Chief inspector Joe Jackson of the
Canadian Aviation Safety Board.
   At the crash site, dozens of investigators tagged blackened
bodies and body parts as they waded through thigh-deep snow to
photograph and probe the wreckage of the Fokker F-28 jet. Both
pilots were among the dead.
   Jackson refused to speculate on the cause of the crash that
occurred shortly after takeoff from Dryden's airport.
   Provincial police said two of the 47 survivors died later in
hospitals. At least eight of the injured were in serious condition,
said provincial police Constable Bill Brayshaw.
   A temporary morgue was set up in a local sports arena in Dryden,
a paper-mill town of 6,500 people about 200 miles northwest of
Duluth, Minn. A police statement said bodies were to be flown Monday
to Toronto for identification.
   Police said 10 bodies were recovered, but their removal from the
crash site was hampered by freezing weather, deep snow and uneven
bushy terrain.
   Purses, one red high heel shoe and a wheel of the aircraft were
among the debris spread through the trees and on the ground near the
wreckage of the airplane. A woman's gray and pink sweater clung to a
birch tree that had been cut in two during the crash.
   The Dutch-built Fokker-28 was headed for Winnipeg, Manitoba, with
65 passengers and a crew of four when it clipped treetops, plowed
into the woods and burst into flames just after taking off in a
snowstorm.
   Some survivors walked out of the woods on their own, many without
coats or shoes in the deep snow.
   ``All we saw was snow and fire and pieces of metal flying,''
passenger Danny Godin told the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. He said
the plane broke apart and, ``Most people were yelling, screaming and
just scrambling.''
   Godin said the plane ``was loaded very heavy. ... We were delayed
in Thunder Bay an hour and we had to take fuel off the airplane
because we were above the legal load limit.''
   ``It was like struggling _ you could hear the (plane)
shuddering,'' said passenger Paul Tagger, 43, of Appleton, Wis., who
escaped with bruises.
   A stewardess, he said, shouted: ``Oh my God, we're going to
crash. Get down! Keep your heads down!''
   Airline vice president Paul McKnight denied the plane was
overloaded.
   The crew members killed included Capt. George Morwood, 52, of
London, Ontario; co-pilot Keith Mills, 35, of Thunder Bay; and
flight attendant Katharine Say, 31, of London. Flight attendant
Sonia Hartwick, 26, of Toronto was not injured.
   Morwood, a 25-year veteran pilot, had been with Air Ontario for
16 years and Mills had been with the airline for 10 years.
   Flight 363 originated in Thunder Bay, an Ontario city on the
north shore of Lake Superior. It made a brief, scheduled stop in
Dryden to pick up passengers and took off about 1 p.m. Friday.
   Norm Pascoe, a spokesman for the Canadian Aviation Safety Board,
said visibility was about half a mile when the plane took off.
   Dryden resident Roxanne Groves heard the aircraft fly overhead.
   ``It didn't sound normal and then all of a sudden we heard a
thump, a good thump. I looked out about five minutes later and there
was black smoke all over the place,'' she said.
   Air Ontario is based in London, Ontario, and is among a number of
rapidly growing commuter airlines providing service to Canada's
scattered towns and cities.
   The last fatal crash in Canada of a regularly scheduled
commercial flight was in 1979, when a Quebecair Fairchild 27 went
down in Quebec City, killing 17 people.
   Canada's worst air disaster occurred in 1985, when 256 people,
mainly American servicemen returning to Kentucky from the Middle
East, died in the crash of a chartered DC-8 in Gander, Newfoundland.
</TEXT>
