<FIRST>r a AM-Vincennes-Iranians     03-11 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Iranians,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Community in San Diego Fears Blame For Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vincennes-Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of San Diego's small Iranian community
say they fear that a suspected terrorist bombing here may add to the
burden of blame they already carry for their roots in the troubled
Middle East.
   A fiery explosion Friday destroyed a van driven by the wife of
Capt. Will Rogers III, who directed the July 1988 missile attack
that mistakenly downed an Iranian airplane in the Persian Gulf.
   The van bombing, which left Sharon Rogers uninjured, has stirred
speculation that the attack was to avenge the deaths of the 290
people aboard the civilian jetliner.
   ``People blame us for everything the ayatollah (Khomeini of Iran)
does, from book-burnings to hijackings,'' said Sara Ahamadianfard,
who came to the United States in 1975 with her husband, a student at
United States International University here.
   ``So it won't surprise me if people assume Iranians had something
to do with this,'' she said.
   Mrs. Rogers received a threatening call after the jetliner's
destruction, Navy Cmdr. David Dillon said. No one has claimed
responsibility for the attack, which is under investigation by
federal authorities.
   Adeeb Nozar Ahmadi, who works at a San Diego grocery store, said
he worries that someone angered by the van bombing might take out
their frustration on him or his young son.
   ``I can tell when some people come into the store that they don't
think I deserve to be here, that I am somehow a terrorist because of
the actions of people I don't even know,'' he said. ``I wonder a lot
what they would do if they got mad enough, if I could become their
victim.''
   Several immigrants in the local Iranian community, estimated at
5,000 in the early 1980s, said they don't necessarily condone
Khomeini's actions, such as the death sentence issued to author
Salman Rushdie for his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``It's like blaming all Germans for the Holocaust,'' said Akbar
Khasravi, an English tutor of Iranian immigrants.
   Khasravi said he abhors any act of violence directed against
innocent people, including Iranians.
   ``Please remember that the people on the jetliner shot down by
the American Navy were innocent, too, just as the woman in the van
was innocent.''
</TEXT>
