<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Pinochet     03-11 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Pinochet,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Expresses Willingness To Consider Opposition Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto SCL-1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet said Saturday
he is willing to consider some constitutional changes sought by the
opposition. Critics suggested he was maneuvering to be allowed to
run in the December elections.
   Small groups of anti-government demonstrators battled with
Pinochet supporters in the downtown streets after the president's
speech at a government office building. Police used water cannons to
stop the fighting and there were no immediate reports of arrests or
serious injuries.
   Pinochet is the army commander who led the coup that ousted the
government of Marxist President Salvador Allende in Sepember 1973
and he has headed the military government since then.
   A constitution drafted by his government was enacted in 1981,
barring a president from succeeding himself. Several opponents said
Pinochet might consider some constitutional reforms in exchange for
an amendment that would permit him to be a presidential candidate in
this year's balloting.
   Pinochet said in his speech that ``the only intention the
government has in indicating its willingness to modify the
constitution is to perfect it.
   ``Our aim is far from the intentions of those who want to
dismantle our institutional structure or those who think that the
president who leads the country is acting with some hidden personal
aim,'' he added.
   After the speech he told a cheering crowd outside the building
that they should unite behind a candidate who would continue his
policies.
   Pinochet lost a referendum in October on a proposal to extend his
rule to 1997. The loss, by a vote of 3.9 million to 3.1 million,
obliged him to call open elections scheduled for Dec. 14. He is to
hand over power to the new government on March 11, 1990.
   Pinochet said in the speech that he had instructed Interior
Minister Carlos Caceres to study several constitutional changes
proposed by opposition groups.
   He said he found ``worthy of study'' suggestions that would
modify an article banning Marxism, shorten the planned eight-year
presidential term and eliminate the president's emergency power to
send citizens into exile.
   Opponents said the changes are needed to ensure democracy when an
elected government takes office. The amendments would have to be
approved in a national referendum.
   Pinochet said he also would consider changes to shorten the
presidential term and erase the president's power to dissolve the
House of Deputies and exile opponents.
   Some opposition groups oppose the constitution's provision for a
presidential term of eight years. Before the 1973 coup the president
served for six years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
