<FIRST>r a AM-Vincennes-Rogers     03-11 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Rogers,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rogers Lived Quiet, Suburban Life _ Till Friday</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vincennes-Bomb Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capt. Will Rogers and his wife Sharon had
settled into a quiet lifestyle where the mistaken destruction of an
Iranian airliner was rarely discuess, friends said. But with the
bombing of Mrs. Roger's van, all that changed.
   The couple's home and neighboring houses and cars immediately
were searched following Friday's bombing which destroyed Mrs.
Roger's Toyota van, as federal investigators sought clues to
determine if terrorism had been behind the blast. Mrs. Rogers
escaped unharmed.
   The FBI said the couple was under guard and in seclusion
Saturday. Protection was offered to their son, who attends college
in upstate New York.
   Whether or not the bombing was the act of terrorists seeking
revenge for Iranian deaths, the event had come home just as
neighbors and friends had feared.
   ``We watched her every single day,'' said Mary Petrou, who lives
across the street from the Roger's home in suburban University City.
   Mrs. Petrou said she set her son's alarm clock so that he would
wake up in time to see Mrs. Roger's leave for work and make sure she
was OK.
   They and other neighbors knew the threats of revenge that
followed the mistaken shooting in July of the airliner by the USS
Vincennes, commanded by Rogers in the Persian Gulf. All 290 people
aboard the plane died.
   Capt. Rogers returned home in October and told reporters he
regretted the loss of lives, but added, ``My absolute responsibility
was for the safety of my ship and crew.''
   Even close friends said the couple hadn't spoken about the
incident since.
   Neighbor George Petrou, who called the Rogers ``good people,''
said they ``never talk shop.''
   ``We talked for happiness, not for business,'' Petrou said. ``But
he is a tough guy, a good soldier.''
   Petrou said he gave the couple some strawberries just before they
left for work. ``When they left, about 7:30, they were laughing and
smiling, and they drove down the street together.''
</TEXT>
