<FIRST>r a AM-US-Israel-PLO     03-11 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Israel-PLO,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis, Palestinians Meet In New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of miles from the Middle East conflict,
a group of Palestinians and Israelis sat down together Saturday to
begin discussions on common goals for peace.
   Officials from the PLO, liberal members of Israel's parliament
and a leading representative from the occupied territories joined
with Arab- and Jewish-American leaders for the symposium at Columbia
University.
   The symposium, sponsored by the Israeli journal New Outlook and
the Palestinian weekly Al Fajr, along with U.S. groups, was based on
principles including the mutual right to self-determination,
renunciation of violence and support for an international peace
conference to include both the Israeli government and the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   There was also to be discussion on resolving conflicts, such as
the 15-month uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip that has
claimed the lives of almost 400 Palestinians and 17 Israelis.
   While there would be much discussion, there would be no
unexpected announcements or concessions, said Nabil Shaath, chairman
of the Political Committee of the Palestine National Council, the
legislative arm of the PLO.
   ``There is a lot to do before we are asked again for new
concessions,'' Shaath said Saturday before the meetings began.
   The major concession _ the PLO's recognition of the state of
Israel's right to exist _ has already been made, he said.
   Yossi Sarid, a Knesset member in the left-wing Citizens Rights
Movement, said that regardless of the outcome ``the success is the
very existence of this meeting.''
   Sarid noted polls that show about 55 percent of Israelis support
holding talks with the PLO, yet 90 percent believe the PLO is a
threat to Israel. ``The PLO must search its own soul _ why don't
people believe it?'' he said.
   Also in New York were Knesset members Ran Cohen, Shulamit Aloni
and Yair Tsaban. They have parliamentary immunity from an Israeli
law barring Israeli citizens from meeting with PLO officials.
   Also scheduled to attend was Faisal Husseini, a top PLO supporter
in the occupied lands.
   Three Palestinians, Shaath, Noha Tadross, a member of the PLO's
Foreign Affairs Department in Tunis, and Afif Safieh, PLO
representative to the Netherlands, were granted waivers to a U.S.
law that generally prohibits visas to PLO members.
   Safieh said the New York meeting was a continuation of a series
of gatherings, including one in Paris and one in the Hague.
</TEXT>
