<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 2211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Baker-Debt     03-11 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Debt,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Baker's Third World Debt Plan May Have Violated Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III may have
violated a Justice Department conflict of interest ruling while he
was treasury secretary in 1987, The Boston Sunday Globe reported.
   The Globe, in Sunday's editions, said Baker rejected a proposal
to force U.S. commercial banks to forgive a large portion of
Brazil's debt while he owned stock in one of the banks.
   The newspaper's report came nearly a month after Baker appeared
to have put the controversy over his holdings in Chemical New York
Corp. behind him. After the issue arose early last month, Baker
quickly moved to silence critics by selling those assets as well as
all other publicly traded stocks that he held in a blind trust.
   Members of Congress noted at the time that Baker had acted on
Third World loan issues while treasury secretary under President
Reagan. Baker was credited with developing the ``Baker plan,'' which
called on Third World nations to make good on their debts.
   According to the Globe, it was at a September 1987 meeting with
Brazil's finance minister that Baker, who at the time owned an
estimated $2 million in Chemical Bank stock, rejected that country's
proposal to restructure some of its $70 billion debt to U.S. banks.
   Chemical Bank has lent $4.5 million to Third World nations,
Brazil among them.
   Three months before Baker took the action, his general counsel
received a Justice Department ruling that high-ranking federal
officials should not take part in any decisions effecting their
personal finances, the Globe said.
   A subsequent study by a economics professor at Stanford
University said Baker's decision had a positive effect on the market
value of the bank's stock. The stock's value rose 40 percent in the
first six months after the decision, from $20 to $28 a share.
   D. Edward Wilson Jr., the Treasury Department's former deputy
general counsel, said that in retrospect, he probably should have
warned Baker about the possible conflict.
   ``If there was a screw-up, it was mine,'' Wilson, now a private
attorney, said Saturday. ``He probably should have been warned there
was a potential problem there.''
   Robert M. Kimmitt, then the Treasury Department's general
counsel, said last week that Baker's participation in the Brazil
decision had been cleared by the department's ethics officer.
   Miklos Lonkay, the ethics officer who cleared Baker's
participation in the Brazil decision, confirmed that he advised
Kimmitt, now Baker's general counsel at the State Department, that
Baker was not required to remove himself from Third World debt
issues generally.
   Like Wilson, however, Lonkay said he did not know the specifics
of the Brazil proposal.
   The Justice Department ruling said the federal
conflict-of-interest law should be interpreted as prohibiting
officials from participating in any ``rulemaking and general policy
matters'' if their decision would have a ``direct and predictable''
effect on their personal holdings.
   C. Boyden Gray, the White House counsel, stressed the Justice
Department ruling as his principal argument in persuading a
reluctant Baker to divest himself of his Chemical stock last month,
the Globe said.
   Baker said he was selling the stock to avoid the perception of a
conflict of interest.
   Wilson said he and other lawyers in the Treasury office had
examined the ruling and concluded that it was unlikely Baker could
set a policy or make a single decision that would have a direct
effect on his holdings in Chemical.
   ``I checked every meeting Baker had to make sure that there was
no chance'' a potential conflict-of-interest problem ``might
arise,'' Wilson said. ``On this one, I must have overlooked'' how
much Brazil owed Chemical, he told the newspaper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
