<FIRST>u a AM-Vincennes-Sessions     03-11 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Sessions,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sessions Says San Diego Bombing Not A Terrorism Trend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William Sessions said
Saturday that the bombing of a van owned by the wife of the USS
Vincennes commander does not signal the beginning of a new frontier
for international terrorism.
   ``I don't think we're seeing a trend at all,'' he said, referring
to the explosion that destroyed the van of the wife of Navy Capt.
Will Rogers III, who mistakenly ordered the destruction of an
Iranian passenger jet.
   ``We are deeply concerned about that kind of activity _ whether
it is in fact a terrorist act,'' Sessions said at a news conference.
``You just can't tell at this stage.''
   Sessions didn't offer new information on the FBI's investigation
into the explosion Friday that Sharon Rogers escaped unhurt. But
investigators have speculated the bombing was to avenge the 290
people killed in the Vincennes' destruction of an Iranian jetliner
last July.
   Sessions said there is no direct evidence that it was a terrorist
bombing, and he said it may be some time before FBI investigators
are able to determine that.
   ``It is always troubling and, of course, the FBI pays very
careful attention on all those investigations because they are all
very important, because terrorism is a very disturbing and very
divisive and difficult matter to deal with,'' he added.
   Counterterrorism has been a priority with the FBI for the past
six years and will continue to be so, said Sessions, who would not
acknowledge that the nation has become more vulnerable to terrorist
acts.
   ``Both the domestic terrorism investigations and the
international terrorism investigations have had a great deal of
effect on our ability to curtail terroristic acts in the United
States.
   ``At the same time, international terrorism last year suffered
some 875 different incidents, of which about 25 percent involved
American citizens.''
   Sessions, a former U.S. attorney and federal judge, addressed
Drake University Law School students Saturday night.
</TEXT>
