<FIRST>u a AM-PLO-Israel     03-11 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-Israel,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Bush To Ask Israel And PLO To Ease Tension In Mideast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush Administration, seeking to lay the
foundation for peace talks, plans to ask the Palestine Liberation
Organization and Israel to to reduce tension in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, a newspaper reported.
   In its Sunday editions, The New York Times quoted a senior Bush
administration official who said specific suggestions for Israel
will be presented Monday when Israel's foreign minister, Moshe
Arens, meets with President Bush and members of his staff.
   The administration official told the newspaper that suggestions
for the PLO will be presented to the PLO through the American
ambassador in Tunis, Robert Pelletreau, Jr.
   The suggestions the Bush administration is expected to put
forward to the Israeli government include ending or limiting
administrative detention of Palestinians, reopening schools in the
occupied territories and releasing some Palestinians involved in the
15-month uprising against the Israelis.
   The PLO is expected to be asked to end all violent demonstrations
in the territories, block anti-Israeli raids from southern Lebanon
and stop distributing inflammatory leaflets.
   The newspaper said Bush hopes the suggestions will be the first
steps toward peace talks between Israel and the PLO. However, the
administration official said the Bush proposal does not include a
full-fledged peace plan.
   One senior State Department official said the Bush plan comes
from the conviction that ``peace in the Middle East cannot be made
in America. In the last analysis the parties out there have to make
the tough decisions and all we can do is help them lay the proper
foundations and build the proper frame as they go along.''
   The senior administration official said the president will move
slowly and ``only move when we think there is a reasonable chance of
success.''
   The newspaper also said Israel will be asked to ease some of the
economic restrictions it has imposed on Palestinians from the West
Bank and Gaza who have not paid their taxes since the uprisings
began in December 1987.
   Palestinians who have not paid taxes cannot obtain identity
cards, drivers licenses or travel permits.
   The administration official said it could be difficult for the
PLO to convince Palestinians that concessions on their part would
improve the chances for peace in the area.
</TEXT>
