<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Haitians     03-11 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Haitians,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>23 Haitians Reported Killed When Boat Capsizes Off Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overcrowded boat loaded with Haitians
trying to reach the United States capsized off the east coast of
Cuba, leaving 23 dead, the official Cuban news service Prensa Latina
said Saturday.
   There were 166 Haitians aboard the Archaie when it sank off the
coast of Holguin province, according to a Prensa Latina dispatch
monitored in Mexico City.
   The news service blamed bad weather for the accident. It did not
say when the accident occurred and provided few other details.
   Cuban authorities helped rescue the survivors, who were being
given medical attention, clothing and other care, Prensa Latina said.
   The news service said Cuban authorities would investigate the
accident and help identify the victims.
   Haiti, the poorest nation in the Western Hemisphere, is on the
island of Hispaniola about 100 miles east of Cuba. Migrants trying
to reach the United States must sail past Cuba's northeast coast to
reach Florida or the Bahamas.
   The Prensa Latina dispatch quoted the Cuban National Information
Agency as saying a similiar accident occurred off the Cuban coast in
the past year, but did not provide any further details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
