<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 2351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Afghan-Missiles     03-11 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Missiles,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Devising Plan to Buy Stingers Back From Afghan Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, fearful that hundreds of
Stinger missiles it sold to Afghan rebels may fall into the hands of
private arms dealers or terrorists, is devising a plan to buy back
the weapons, The New York Times reported.
   The Times in its Sunday editions said, however, that senior
administration believe it may be an impossible task to persuade the
rebels to return even some of the Stingers.
   At an interagency meeting Wednesday at the White House headed by
Robert Graves, the deputy national security adviser, the CIA was
given the task of developing a strategy for the Stinger recovery,
the newspaper reported.
   The United States may try to barter state-of-the-art irrigation
equipment, trucks, tractors and medical facilities as well as sheep
and mules in exchange for the shoulder-held rockets, according to
the Times.
   The Bush administration also is considering trying to shift
covert military aid approved by Congress into funds for
reconstruction and the return of up to five million refugees.
   Some of these funds would then be set aside for Stinger recovery,
the newspaper said.
   ``It's prudent for the administration to try to recover the
Stingers, but I personally doubt it will succeed,'' said Rep.
Charles Wilson, D-Texas, who was instrumental in persuading the
Reagan administration to give the rebels Stingers.
   Frank C. Carlucci, the former secretary of defense, told the
Times, ``We'll never get them back, never.''
   American intelligence officials estimate the rebels have 200 to
500 Stingers, but have no clear idea what rebel groups have the
weapons or where they are stored, the Times said.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, the Arizona Democrat, said, ``We were
assured that the Stingers were turned over to teams of Afghan
mujahedeen who were identifiable so we could monitor them and get
them back, but I'm fearful that may not be the case.''
   The Stinger is the Army's most advanced infantry anti-aircraft
missile; it is often referred to as the perfect terrorist weapon.
   Since mid-1986, when the first Stingers were delivered to the
rebels, some of them have fallen into the hands of Soviet commandoes
and Iranian revolutionary guards.
   Bush administration officials told the newspaper the United
States will urge Pakistan, which has been responsible for funneling
American military aid to the rebel groups, to help in the Stinger
recovery efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
