<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Bishops-Text     03-11 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Bishops-Text,0918</SECOND>
<HEAD>Text Of Cardinal's Speech To U.S. Bishops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vatican-US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the address given
Friday to U.S. bishops by Cardinal Eduard Gagnon, the president of
the Pontifical Council for the Family:
   INTRODUCTORY REMARKS ON MARRIAGE AND THE FAMILY
   The authentic teaching of the Church has usually to go against
what is commonly promoted in the secularist schools and mass media
(and) is often misunderstood or misrepresented inside the Church
itself.
   It is indeed cumbersome and irritating at times to hear families
complain about what is being taught to their children, ... but
listening to them might be the only way we have to know what is
happening at the grass roots of our Catholic communities and
institutions.
   What happens in your country always has an influence, especially
in the developing countries, but also in Europe.
   ABORTION
   Our Council has witnessed with great interest the progress which
the courageous work of laity and clergy since the Roe vs. Wade
decision has realized in forming consciences and changing
mentalities.
   The American Church has not yet obtained everything it would
desire, but it has demonstrated that even adverse public events can
become a providential occasion for that essential part of
evangelization which is to defend the most fundamental right of the
human person.
   You have made many to understand what is expressed in the Charter
of the Rights of the Family: `Economic aid for the advancement of
peoples must not be conditioned on acceptance of programs of
contraception, sterilization or abortion.'
   The bishops in charge of the family apostate for bishops
conferences in more than 50 countries ... have begged their brother
bishops of politically powerful nations to protect them from the new
form of colonialism which anti-life programs constitute. They are
sure you can do something to defend them.
   PORNOGRAPHY
   I know you are trying to work with all people of good will in
defending youth and adults alike against the danger to their
personhood coming from pornography and the potent industries behind
it.
   I would suggest that we do something too about another and more
subtle pornography, that is the degrading of moral values vehicled
by cinema and TV shows which pretend to depict normal American life.
At a U.N. meeting, a sociologist defined the developed and
underdeveloped nations as those who looked at or could not look at
the Dallas TV series.
   We feel our fellow citizens are adult enough to resist such
poisonous food. But the pastors of other worlds would like us to
reflect on what we export can do to the conscience of their people.
   NATURAL FAMILY PLANNING
   A problem has emerged about which we have to be vigilant. That of
combining Natural Family Planning with methods of artificial
contraception, at times because International Planned Parenthood
Foundation or similar groups try to infiltrate Catholic
associations, and corrupt and pirate N.F.P. methods.
   MARRIAGE INDISSOLUBILITY AND TRIBUNALS
   The prevalent divorce mentality has rendered the role of marriage
tribunals most essential and at the same time most complex.
   We know you are worried about the problems you are confronted
with because of the lack of personnel for the tribunals and the huge
number of broken marriages.
   Women religious can be very helpful in dealing with marriage
cases, but we have to be careful that their tender hearts do not
play tricks on them.
   MARRIAGE PREPARATION AND DOCTRINE
   I think we should not be pessimistic about the possibility of
reversing trends and changing the climate of hostility which has
been prevalent against the Magisterium's doctrine on conjugal
morality.
   The number of good young couples who look for sound spiritual
guidance is much greater than we would think.
   A new challenge is offered to the Church by the efforts of
Planned Parenthood to set up school-based clinics for abortion
referral and contraception. A way to oppose this menace in all
dioceses would be to develop a united policy and practice on a
national level. Planned Parenthood programs of sex education in no
way resolve the problem of teen-age pregnancies, but rather increase
it by encouraging promiscuity. The statistical fact surprisingly
turned up in one of their own surveys.
   OTHER ISSUES
   Another question is the spreading of euthanasia. ... Word
engineering that leads to idea engineering ... could ultimately lead
to legalization of euthanasia, as it has done for abortion.
   A further question is that of the ministry to remarried
divorcees. Some forms of such ministry, ignoring the principles set
in Familias Consortio, have degenerated into dating services for
divorced Catholics who are not free to marry. I know that their
promoters are personages who cannot easily be brought under
episcopal control. Maybe some guidelines coming from your Conference
could help priests and faithful in their discernment.
   It is evident that ideological feminism has a deleterious
influence on the family. But conversely the best way to counter its
influence will be to care more about the family and make every one
in it more conscious of his or her vocation ``to serve and not be
served,'' as Christ has taught us.
   Much is being said here of feminism. I would just like to remark
that when we work, as we should, for the promotion of women, we
should be careful in choosing the persons we work with.
</TEXT>
