<FIRST>r i AM-UN-HumanRights     03-11 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Human Rights,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Ends Session After Votes on Cuba, Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Human Rights Commission ended its 1989
session on Friday with votes on Cuba and Romania, rounding out a
list of more than 100 resolutions and decisions in a six-week
meeting.
   Under a measure backed by Romania's Warsaw Pact ally Hungary and
by all Western and some Third World countries, Romania will come
under a U.N. inquiry for alleged grave human rights abuses.
   In coming under scrutiny, it joins such nations as Chile, El
Salvador, South Africa.
   Relations between communist neighbors Romania and Hungary
deteriorated after Hungary publicly accused Romania of depriving its
ethnic Hungarian minority of their ethnic and cultural rights.
Romania denies it.
   A vaguely worded resolution on Cuba, supported by both the Havana
government and the United States, dashed Washington's hopes of a
continued U.N. surveillance of the human rights situation under the
Fidel Castro government.
   A Western proposal that would have added Iraq to the list of
suspected human rights violators failed to come to a vote. Iraq
blocked it by a procedural motion backed by most Third World
countries, which had a majority in the 43-nation panel.
   The commission approved a draft convention on the rights of
children and a draft protocol designed to promote the abolition of
the death penalty. Both drafts go before next fall's U.N. General
Assembly for a final decision.
</TEXT>
