<FIRST>r a AM-CoastalDamage 1stLd-Writethru   03-11 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coastal Damage, 1st Ld-Writethru,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relentless Northeaster Continues Pounding N.C. Outer Banks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with damage estimates; picks up
2nd graf: ``That's the ...; ADDS 1 graf with Virginia damage estimates.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RHD2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials sealed off beach areas Friday as
gusting wind and waves battered oceanfront cottages and motels, but
the weather service predicted relief from the storm.
   Officials estimate that the storm has inflicted $4.5 million
damage.
   Kitty Hawk was hardest hit, with $2 million in damages reported
by Friday night, said Dare County civil defense officials. Damage at
Nags Head ran to $1.9 million, Kill Devil Hills had $430,000 and
Hatteras Island $200,000.
   ``That's the breaks,'' Ernie McGlothlin said as he watched the
sea batter the beachfront retirement home he bought two years ago.
``I don't know if the whole house is going to go or just the front
half. But if it goes, it goes. There's nothing I can do about it.''
   His house was one of 70 cottages and motels damaged or destroyed
by the storm that kicked up tides and wind, eroding the slender
beaches of the northern Outer Banks of North Carolina.
   When McGlothlin bought his house, a 15-foot sand dune blocked the
view of the ocean from the first floor. A storm last month wiped out
the dune and the waves have crept closer to his foundation all this
week.
   ``First, it took the porch, and we thought, well, maybe it won't
come any further,'' said Marie Coble of Kitty Hawk, a friend who has
helped McGlothlin renovate the home. ``That's when we moved the
furniture to the back of the house. Then the side wall came down and
collapsed the front bedroom. If it comes any further, it could cause
the rest of that end to collapse.''
   A proclamation by Nags Head Mayor Donald Bryan sealing off the
beach was the first of its kind in nine years. It bars pedestrians
and traffic from the beach road in South Nags Head, except for
property owners. It also forbids anyone to enter damaged buildings
along the beach.
   National Weather Service forecasters said the threat might lessen
after Friday as a storm packing 60 mph winds moves to sea. The storm
has battered the coast for three days, causing damages expected to
be in the millions of dollars.
   ``I got to laugh to keep from crying,'' said Kitty Hawk resident
Joseph Verscharen as he and his wife, Janet, surveyed the damage to
their oceanfront lot on Thursday. ``This was our castle.''
   About 10 feet of their cottage hung over a 6-foot cliff where the
ocean had eroded more than 75 feet of beach and a dune the
Verscharens built after storm damage in April.
   Since the storm began Tuesday, North Carolina Power has
disconnected electric lines to 45 endangered residences, primarily
in South Nags Head and Kitty Hawk.
   The high tides had Hatteras Island officials worried about the
Herbert C. Bonner bridge, the only connection between the island's
5,000 residents and Bodie Island. Late Thursday night, officials
said water was sloshing over both ends of the bridge.
   About 75 feet of the Hatteras Island Fishing Pier in Rodanthe
washed away. In Kill Devil Hills, bulkheading supporting the Avalon
Pier was undercut, prompting officials to rope it off.
   But National Park Service officials said the Cape Hatteras
Lighthouse has been spared by a sandbar offshore.
   In Virginia, officials in the Norfolk-Virginia Beach region said
the storm caused five deaths, including a homeless man who died of
exposure Friday, and had caused $776,000 damage to 45 coastal homes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
