<DOCNO> AP890311-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-WhiteHouse-Cambodian Adv13   03-11 0976</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House-Cambodian, Adv 13,1001</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Mon March 13 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cambodian Refugee Finds Top Spot in Bush Administration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As he fled, wounded, through the jungles of
Cambodia, Sichan Siv never could have imagined that in 13 years he
would be a top aide to an American president.
   For Siv, 41, deputy assistant to President Bush for public
liaison, the term American dream is not a cliche. His almost
unbelievable story is the stuff of movies.
   In a symbolic gesture, Siv opted to start his job Feb. 13, the
13th anniversary of his escape from Cambodia. But he said, with a
smile, the highlight of his 4-week-old tenure at the White House
came when he met Bush last week, and the president ``pronounced my
name right.''
   In his new job, one of two deputies in the office, Siv is Bush's
contact with ethnic and minority groups. He deals with issues like
civil rights, education, the homeless and refugees.
   Siv's tortuous path from wounded refugee to presidential aide
began after the Khmer Rouge, a brutal communist insurgency, defeated
the U.S.-backed government of Lon Nol in April 1975.
   Before his escape, Siv rode a bicycle across Cambodia for 20
days, survived in a Khmer Rouge labor camp eating a bowl of rice a
day and worked myriad jobs from dawn to dusk.
   ``I dug irrigation canals. I plowed land. I planted rice. I
harvested rice,'' he said.
   He fled Cambodia 10 months after the Khmer Rouge takeover by
jumping off a timber truck and running through the jungle without
food for three days until he reached Thailand. En route, he stepped
on a land mine.
   About 15 family members, including his mother, were among the
hundreds of thousands of people killed by the Pol Pot regime.
   It was his mother, a Buddhist, whose philosophy helped him
survive, Siv said.
   ``The two things she told me are, `As long as you live you must
always have hope,' and, `Happiness is something you can't keep
unless you give it away.' Those are the basic values of life that I
have always kept with me,'' he said in an interview.
   Siv's new life, working in an ornate, high-ceilinged office at
the White House complex, seems light years away from the Cambodian
bush.
   But Siv, who dresses in pin-striped suits with suspenders and
speaks English with an accent, keeps mementos nearby: native musical
instruments, silver ornaments and books about his native land.
   The son of a policeman, Siv received his high school and college
education in Phnom Penh, Cambodia's capital. Before the capital
fell, he worked with the airline, as a high school teacher and as an
administrator with CARE, the relief organization.
   He was supposed to be evacuated from the U.S. Embassy by
helicopter, but missed the last flight out on April 12, 1975 by 30
minutes. It took him until the following February to make his break.
   During that time, Siv was forced to conceal his education from
the Khmer Rouge, who were determined to stamp out the intelligensia.
And his decision to get to the Thai-Cambodian border meant a
traumatic separation from his family.
   Arriving in Thailand, Siv was jailed as an illegal entrant, but
was later released and placed in a refugee camp. There, a Catholic
relief group found a couple in Wallingford, Conn., willing to
sponsor Siv. He arrived in the United States with $2 in his pocket.
   ``He's a person with a great deal of charisma,'' said Bob
Charles, the Wallingford man who brought Siv to this country.
Charles is a housing consultant.
   With nothing to his name, Siv picked apples and worked in an ice
cream parlor before New York City beckoned. There he drove a taxi
cab for six months, and, later got a job with the Lutheran
Immigration and Refugee Service.
   Eager to improve his lot, Siv won a scholarship from Columbia
University where he obtained a master's degree in international
affairs. Degree in hand, Siv worked at the United Nations and for
the Institute for International Education.
   Siv also a Texas connection through his wife, Martha, a United
Nations librarian from Pampa, Texas. ``I'm the honorary mayor of
Pampa,'' Siv said, proudly displaying a key to the city. Married in
1983, the couple has no children.
   In 1987, Siv went to work for Bush as, he says, ``one of the many
faceless volunteers'' in New York. He raised money and made contacts
with the Asian community.
   Once Bush was elected, Chase Untermeyer, a Texan who heads the
White House personnel office, recommended Siv for his present job.
John Sununu, the White House chief of staff, and David Demarest, the
communications director, approved the hiring.
   ``I was impressed not only with the substance and drama of his
backround, but also his political acumen, his character and his
obvious knowledge of how to get things done, and a drive and
stick-to-it-iveness that you need in the job he's got,'' Demarest
said.
   Court Robinson, an analyst with the U.S. Committee for Refugees
who knows Siv, said the new White House aide has focused heavily on
Cambodian issues. But refugees like Siv often have a keen interest
in the domestic issues of their adopted country, he said. ``He's
always struck me as bright and articulate,'' Robinson said.
   Siv attributes his rise to his adaptability. ``I have been
fortunate to get myself adjusted into new situations very quickly,''
he said.
   Hard work is another must for the upwardly mobile. Siv said he
has promised himself he won't work more than 13 hours on weekdays
and 10 hours on the weekend.
   ``It doesn't matter how many hours I put in ... there is no
single minute that is boring or dull,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
