<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Metropolis, Adv 14, 1st-ld Writethru b0493,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues AMs, March 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, ``Metropolis is a ...,'' to correct second reference
to Maria, changing to Futura; corrects Freeman, sted Freedman, throughout.</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Musical ``Metropolis'' Comes To Life In London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Fritz Lang had known that his 1926 film
``Metropolis'' would become a musical, he might have laughed.
   Perhaps Victor Hugo would have also. After all, if Hugo's epic
19th-century novel ``Les Miserables'' could become a hit musical,
why not Lang's classic vision of the future?
   ``I think `Les Miz' is the best thing ever; that's what I'd like
our show to live up to,'' said Joseph Brooks, who wrote the Grammy
award-winning song ``You Light Up My Life,'' from the 1977 movie of
that name.
   ``Metropolis,'' which opened in London March 8, cost 2.5 million
pounds ($4.38 million), and is the first of several large-scale
musicals to open this year in London.
   Its bow at the Piccadilly Theater follows a bad period for
British musical productions in 1988, when ``Chess'' and ``Carrie''
flopped on Broadway and ``Can-Can,'' ``Budgie'' and ``Ziegfeld''
died in London.
   Brooks has co-written the music, book and lyrics of
``Metropolis.'' Frenchman Jerome Savary, who staged a hit Paris
revival of ``Cabaret'' in 1986, is directing, with choreography by
Tom Jobe, the American who starred in ``Chess'' in London.
   Brian Blessed, the original Old Deuteronomy in ``Cats,'' heads
the cast as John Freeman, the evil master of the machine-age
metropolis where the action takes place. The romantic leads are
played by Graham Bickley and Judy Kuhn, who was nominated for a Tony
for her role in the American production of ``Chess,'' in a show
that, despite its emphasis on technology, aims to put emotion first.
   ``I'm hopeful that the music and the emotional content of what we
want to say are what will be taken home,'' said Brooks.
   Brooks moved to London in 1985 with his wife and two children,
intending to write a musical, and he was searching for strongly
visual material that would transfer well to the stage.
   His wife, Susan, asked the British Film Institute for a list of
its movies, Brooks recalled. When the title ``Metropolis'' appeared,
her reaction was, ``That's the film.'' A series of screenings
ensued, followed by negotiations with the Fritz Lang estate in
Vienna.
   ``Metropolis'' is a stupefying tale about workers in a
modernistic city who live underground. A sweet girl named Maria
soothes their unrest until a mad scientist creates an artificial
evil Maria who leads the workers to revolt. The silent film, a
benchmark of German expressionism, was reissued in 1984 with a
colored tint and a score by Giorgio Moroder.
   The play is Brooks' first writing for the theater. He composed
the music for the films ``Marjoe,'' ``The Garden of the
Finzi-Continis'' and ``The Lords of Flatbush,'' and has written over
140 advertising jingles, mostly for television.
   ``I grew up in Manhattan loving all the old standards:
`Carousel,' `Oklahoma!' They all had tremendous melodies; that's
what I've tried to do.''
   But the initial appeal of ``Metropolis'' may well lie in its
scenery, which takes up one-third of the musical's budget. Its
massive gray-and-black, pipe-filled sets evoke an oppressively cold,
mechanistic environment populated by two worlds _ the underground
one of the two lovers and the elitist one ruled by the evil inventor
(Freeman).
   Brooks and his colleagues dispute suggestions that ``Metropolis''
is another British techno-spectacle such as ``Cats'' and ``Starlight
Express.''
   ``If ever a show required a big visual statement, it's this
one,'' said Ralph Koltai, the Hungarian designer responsible for the
ill-fated ``Carrie'' and a frequent collaborator at the Royal
Shakespeare Company. ``You couldn't do `Metropolis' on an empty
stage with a chair.''
   Judy Kuhn, who makes her West End debut as the saintly Maria,
said: ``This show is about machines; it's about what man has created.
   ``As long as technology helps the show, it's OK. It's technology
for its own sake that's the problem.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues AMs, March 14</NOTE>
