<DOCNO> AP890311-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv13   03-11 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 13,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday March 13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eastern Bondholders May Be Hoping For A Piece Of The Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple of flotation cushions, a slice of wing
or a cone-shaped metallic nose can make for interesting garden
sculpture and spell satisfaction of sorts for some of Eastern
Airlines' bondholders.
   Now that the strike-crippled carrier is operating under
bankruptcy court protection, hard assets may be the bondholders'
best hope for repayment with more than 15,000 creditors in line for
cash.
   Roughly 25 percent of Eastern's total liabilities of $4.1 billion
are in the form of ``equipment trust certificates,'' which as the
name implies are backed by equipment.
   Holders of these issues, commonly used by transportation
companies, can repossess Eastern's planes under certain
circumstances if the carrier defaults on its interest payments.
   Out of a gamut of creditors ranging from ticket holders to
employees in demand of paychecks, trust certificate holders ``are
clearly in a favorable position,'' said Mike Singer, director of
research at R.D. Smith &amp; Co., a firm specializing in the securities
of ``distressed'' companies.
   Unlike unsecured creditors and shareholders _ whose financial
exposure is not backed by collateral and are therefore last in line
to get paid if a company defaults _ trust certificates are ``good
for bondholders because they have a pool of equipment to back them
up if there is a liquidation,'' said Raymond Neidl, a senior
securities analyst at McCarthy, Crisanti &amp; Maffei, Inc.
   The market reflected that optimism. When a company seeks Chapter
11 protection from its creditors, bond prices generally are knocked
down. And under these stressful circumstances, major bond-rating
agencies are prompted to lower their ratings on debt securities,
further adding to the downward momentum of prices.
   But although both Moody's and Standard &amp; Poor's lowered their
ratings on much of Eastern's debt, there was little backlash.
   Bond traders apparently had jumped the gun, pushing Eastern's
debt issues down as much as 10 percent in value in the weeks leading
up to the Chapter 11 filing. So when the news came Thursday that
Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp., was
sending Eastern into bankruptcy protection, bond trading was
relatively unaffected.
   ``There were a lot of low-ball bids, but there were no takers,''
Neidl said. Indeed, Eastern's secured and unsecured bonds lost only
2 percent to 4 percent of their face value that day, not an erosion
that dealers and analysts would consider significant.
   That's because the bankruptcy filing was ``not exactly a total
shock,'' Singer said. Furthermore, ``there is a lot of value in
Eastern one way or another, so its securities should only drop so
far from a psychological aspect, but the fundamentals show that
creditors will get meaningful values for their bonds. Just how much
will be determined by the bankruptcy proceedings.''
   Based on its assets, Eastern might be worth as much as $3.55
billion, according to some analysts' estimates. The figure includes
the carrier's 250-plane fleet, valued at roughly $2.5 billion.
   Lorenzo and other Eastern executives have worked doggedly at
press conferences and in interviews to make assurances that all
creditors will be paid. Their efforts have had at least some calming
effect.
   There is a fear, however, that Eastern blood may spill onto its
corporate parent, Texas Air, and sister carrier Continental. The two
main Wall Street debt-rating services announced they are keeping a
sharp eye Texas Air and Continental for possible downgradings.
   Moody's said Eastern's bankruptcy filing has an ``uncertain
effect'' on each company and noted the possibilty that Texas Air
could be drawn into the proceedings.
   For Eastern bondholders, however, the situation does not appear
terribly grim, analysts said. ``The next stage is to see how
successful (Lorenzo) is in rebuilding'' Eastern, Neidl said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
