<FIRST>r f BC-Infotech     03-11 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Infotech,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infotech Completes WNW Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Infotechnology Inc., a holding company with
interests in scientific and information ventures, has completed its
acquisition of the company that controls United Press International.
   New York-based Infotech said Thursday it issued roughly 1.5
million shares of common stock it valued at about $16.15 million in
return for the 80 percent of WNW Group Inc. it did not already own.
   Infotech Chairman Earl W. Brian created WNW a year ago to take
control of UPI from Mexican publisher Mario Vasquez Rana. It does
not own the news service outright, but WNW controls how UPI shares
are voted and retains an irrevocable option to buy the news service.
   Meanwhile, the Dutch investment partnership Avacus Partners LP
said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission on
Wednesday that it has increased its stake in Infotech from 8.03
percent to 9.27 percent.
   Avacus said it has discussed takeover financing with ``a major
money center bank'' and that it might sell off all or part of
Infotech to finance a takeover. Avacus also said it may protest the
WNW purchase, claiming it dilutes Infotech's stock.
   Infotech spokeswoman Amber Gordon noted that the stock
transaction with WNW was not a defensive measure to ward off an
unwanted takeover and had been contemplated for some time.
   Infotech has wide-ranging holdings of medical, scientific and
information companies including two cable television channels,
Financial News Network and The Learning Channel.
</TEXT>
