<FIRST>r f AM-AutoPrices     03-11 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Prices,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan Boosts Prices on Two-Door Pathfinder by $1,500</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average price of a two-door Nissan Pathfinder
sport-utility vehicle will increase $1,500 effective Monday because
of a higher tariff on the Japanese-made vehicle, the company said
Friday.
   Thomas D. Mignanelli, executive vice president for operations of
Nissan Motor Corp. in U.S.A., said in a news release that the
company will absorb some of the higher tariff, but most of it would
be passed on to the customer.
   On Feb. 16, the U.S. Treasury Department issued a list of
vehicles it classified as trucks, and subject to a 25 percent duty,
and cars, for which importers had to pay a 2.5 percent tariff.
   The two-door Pathfinder fell in the truck category.
   ``We regret being forced to take this action,'' Mignanelli said
Friday, ``but the Treasury Department's decision left us no
recourse. Nissan still believes the ruling is an unnecessary and
unwarranted tax on consumers.''
   Nissan continues to hold out the possibility that production of
the two-door Pathfinder could be moved from Japan to the company's
plant in Smyrna, Tenn., removing the tariff charge.
   But company spokesman Bill Pauli said Friday no decision has been
reached on that.
   A four-door version of the Pathfinder, which the Treasury
Department classifies as a car and subject to a 2.5 percent duty, is
to be introduced in late autumn or early winter, Pauli added.
</TEXT>
