<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Sotheby's     03-11 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Sotheby's,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sotheby's Posts Big Profit Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's Holdings Inc., the parent company of the
auction house, said Friday its fourth-quarter profit more than
doubled from a year ago, primarily because of strong auction sales.
   Sotheby's said net income for the three months came to $31.4
million, or $1.11 a share, compared with $15 million, or 59 cents a
share, in the same period a year ago.
   Operating revenue jumped 45 percent to $143.1 million from $99
million, it said.
   For the year, net income rose 60 percent to $61.9 million, or
$2.20 a share, from $38.7 million, or $1.54 a share, in 1987.
   Twelve-month operating revenue rose 25 percent to $349 million
from $279 million.
   Michael Ainslie, president of Sotheby's Holdings, said the strong
auction sales, particularly in paintings, as well as good returns
from the company's financing arm contributed to the profits surge.
