<FIRST>r f AM-US-Japan-Construction     03-11 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan-Construction,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tishman Forms Joint Venture To Build In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tishman Realty &amp; Construction Co. Inc. said
Friday it would become the first U.S. company to launch a
construction project in Japan's private sector since an agreement to
open Japan to American builders was reached last May.
   Tishman said its Japanese arm would form a joint venture with
Japan's Aoki Corp. to build a 400-room, $200 million luxury
high-rise hotel in Osaka, to be operated by Westin Hotels &amp; Resorts.
   Construction is scheduled to begin in April 1990 and be completed
in March 1993. Tishman and Aoki will serve jointly as construction
managers while Aoki serves as general contractor.
   The agreement signed by U.S. and Japanese officials in May 1988
called for Japan to encourage foreign participation in major public
works projects financed by the Japanese government and other
projects carried out by Japanese companies with funding from both
the local and central governments.
   One aspect of the agreement was to make it easier for American
firms to get construction licenses in Japan. Tishman Construction
Corp. of Japan got a license in October to do both public- and
private-sector work.
</TEXT>
