<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Brazil-WorldBank     03-11 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Brazil-World Bank,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank Offers Brazil $1 Billion For Electricity Development</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank offered the country $1
billion for electric power development, the Planning Ministry said
Friday.
   The bank's representative for Brazil, Armeane Choksi, proposed
the loan in a meeting Thursday with Planning Minister Joao Batista
de Abreu, the ministry said.
   Last year, the World Bank suspended payment of an approved $500
million loan for the electric power sector after Brazil put its
nuclear program under the aegis of the state electric company.
   The bank questioned the economic feasibility of the proposed
Angra III nuclear plant, which hasn't been built yet. However, many
Brazilian believe the real problem was environmental concerns
regarding the nuclear plant and proposed hydrolectric dams in the
Amazon rain forest.
   The suspension of the loan led foreign private banks to withhold
$600 million in new loans, part of an $82.2 billion loan package
approved last September. The new money was tied to the release of
the World Bank loan.
   President Jose Sarney has vowed to cut government spending as
part of an economic reform program announced Jan. 15 to halt 1,000
percent annual inflation.
   Abreu called the offers ``positive'' and stressed the importance
of ``reversing the negative flow'' of funds from Brazil to the World
Bank. The government currently pays the bank more than it receives.
</TEXT>
