<DOCNO> AP890311-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Bankruptcy-HealthyFirms Adv12   03-11 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bankruptcy-Healthy Firms, Adv 12,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday March 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chapter 11 Bankruptcy Filings Not Always by Companies in the Red</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies like Eastern Airlines usually file for
bankruptcy protection after years of losses. But some of the most
prominent Chapter 11 filings over the past decade have been by
companies running in the black.
   When Texaco Inc., the nation's third-largest oil company, asked a
federal bankruptcy court to protect it from creditors in April 1987,
it was solvent. So was Manville Corp. when it filed for bankruptcy
reorganization in August 1982 and A.H. Robins Co. Inc. when it filed
in August 1985.
   The difference between these cases and the more common bankruptcy
court filings by companies going broke is the three firms were
trying to avoid the possibility of future financial ruin from
massive legal claims.
   By filing under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law, a
company can reorganize its business protected from claims by
creditors, including legal claimants.
   Texaco filed for bankruptcy protection because of a $10.3 billion
judgment won against the oil giant by Pennzoil Co. in 1985. Pennzoil
had charged Texaco with interfering with Pennzoil's plans to acquire
Getty Oil Co.
   Texaco said it filed for protection to avoid having to post a
potentially devastating $11 billion security bond required under
Texas law during the appeals process.
   But, more importantly, the filing put pressure on Pennzoil to
settle the dispute.
   Without a settlement, Texaco's reorganization could have become a
drawn-out process and Pennzoil might not have seen any money for
years. With their $3 billion agreement, the reorganization plan was
wrapped up a year after Texaco's filing.
   Manville and Robins each were facing thousands of claims from
individuals _ Manville from people made ill by its asbestos
products, and Robins from women injured by its Dalkon Shield
intrauterine birth control device.
   Both companies said they would be wiped out if they had to pay
all the claims facing them. Their filings were a form of damage
control.
   Manville's bankruptcy court filing was considered novel when it
was first made. The company emerged from bankruptcy protection last
November. Its reorganization plan provided for up to 200,000
asbestos claimants to share in a $3 billion trust fund set up to
compensate.
   The Robins plan, which is pending, provides $2.5 billion to
settle nearly 200,000 claims.
   None of these companies had lost money because of the claims
against them.
   Eastern, however, had verged on a bankruptcy filing for years.
The airline said in court papers it had lost $1.02 billion this
decade. It listed $4.5 billion in assets, $3.39 billion in
liabilities, and 15,696 creditors.
   The bankruptcy filing was triggered and complicated by a walkout
by mechanics, pilots and flight attendants a week ago.
   At first blush, Eastern's filing may seem totally different from
cases like Texaco, Manville or Robins. But Richard D'Aveni, a
professor at Dartmouth's College Amos Tuck School of Business
Administration, saw some similarities.
   A bankruptcy filing is leverage, whether it's used by a company
like Texaco, seeking an advantage over a single opponent, or by a
firm like Eastern, trying to work its way out of a tangle of red
ink, D'Aveni said.
   ``It's one way to bargain with and reallocate the power among the
stakeholders,'' D'Aveni said in an interview.
   ``That's the purpose of the bankuptcy law,'' he said.
   Even in a Manville or Robins situation, where a company is facing
thousands of claims, a filing forces the company and creditors into
negotiations. In such cases, thousands of claimants against a
company are joined into a class represented by the same attorneys.
   In a case like Texaco's, the bankruptcy law has another advantage
_ it can be used as a way around the heavy financial penalties meted
out by antitrust laws, D'Aveni said.
   He considered it likely that more companies would file under
Chapter 11 when faced with claims similar to those faced by these
companies.
   He was right. It happened again this past week.
   Raytech Corp., a manufacturing holding company, filed for
protection from creditors on Friday. The company has been named a
co-defendant in more than 1,000 lawsuits brought by people claiming
to have been injured by asbestos used in the past by one of the
company's businesses.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday March 12</NOTE>
