<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f AM-Eastern-MasterPlan Adv12   03-11 1145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Master Plan, Adv 12,1177</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, March 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Frank Lorenzo's Aim: Make Money, Corner the Industry Through Texas
Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soon after adding Eastern Airlines to his
collection of wayward carriers, Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank
Lorenzo boasted in 1986 that he had envisioned the possibility of
Eastern seeking bankruptcy protection.
   To prevent the drain of Texas Air assets to Eastern in times of
need, the man who shrunk Continental Airlines and broke its unions
after a similar takeover devised a setup keeping Eastern financially
independent of its parent.
   He bragged that the only ties between the airlines were Texas
Air's initial cash outlay and some dividends guaranteed after four
years. But he predicted ``thrashing'' and ``changes'' in those four
years, implying those 1990 payments wouldn't ever happen.
   ``Eastern could go into Chapter 11 and it would not affect what
we do,'' Lorenzo said, according to a transcript of a December 1986
meeting with pilots. ``Having said that, I don't think the Eastern's
going to go into Chapter 11. I think the unions are going to
negotiate because I think they realize that the last place they want
to be is in Chapter 11.''
   Of course, the aggressive Machinists union didn't negotiate and
was joined by pilots in a walkout Eastern claims forced it to seek
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy law
last week.
   Critics say Lorenzo, the one-time wonder boy of the airline
industry unions now label a ``robber baron,'' isn't fazed by the
prospect of bankruptcy after a 17-month management-labor slugfest.
   They say Chapter 11 may indeed be the last place the unions want
to be because it gives Lorenzo a chance to bust them and slash the
assets of an airline $2.5 billion in debt, possibly consolidating
Eastern and Continental.
   And they detect a pattern in Frank Lorenzo's 20 years in the
industry _ the piecemeal acquisition of components in building the
dominant megacarrier in the age of deregulation.
   To Lorenzo, making money _ not sentimental attachments to
airlines like Eastern, one of the nation's four original majors _ is
what has mattered.
   ``He is in the money business, not the airline business. In the
airline business you have to be people-oriented,'' said Paul Gibson
Jr., an American Airlines vice president in the 1970s and
early-1980s who now practices law in New York.
   How did Lorenzo, the 48-year-old son of Spanish immigrants,
manage to build Texas Air from a tiny intra-state flier mockingly
dubbed Tree Top Airlines into the nation's largest carrier?
   Lorenzo and a Harvard Business School classmate pooled about
$2,000 in 1966 to form Jet Capital Corp, an aircraft leasing company
Lorenzo critics say was little more than an excuse for an office in
New York's Pan Am Building.
   Tiny Jet Capital in 1972 bought a controlling interest in Trans
Texas Airlines, renamed it Texas Air International _ thanks to a
single border hop into Mexico _ and Lorenzo became president.
   Lorenzo exploited federal regulation to get loans for planes to
expand Texas Air's fleet. Long before deregulation, the airline
offered discount rates Lorenzo called ``Peanut Fares'' and got
national attention.
   In 1978 Lorenzo tried to acquire National Airlines, then a major
carrier. The action triggered a bidding war among the major
airlines, and Pan Am eventually outbid rivals for the airline, but
not before Lorenzo made about $40 million from the sale of National
stock.
   ``It was a fear of deregulation and Pan Am had to get a domestic
route system,'' said one longtime airline industry official with no
love for Lorenzo. ``It literally wrecked the airline.''
   In 1980, Lorenzo tried to buy Trans World Airlines and formed
non-union New York Air to compete with Eastern on the East Coast.
The empire grew.
   The post-deregulation era was one of the shakiest in the
industry. But in 1982, during a time of high fuel costs, airline
consolidation and low passenger demand, Lorenzo grabbed beleaguered
Continental _ which lost $100 million the year before _ and its
Midwest strength for $100 million.
   Despite cash reserves of about $80 million, Lorenzo took
Continental into bankruptcy in 1983, abrogated union contracts, cut
staff by two-thirds, flew through a strike and emerged with a
non-union airline _ and the ire of labor.
   ``He was one of the first to recognize that in order to reduce
fares he had to reduce costs from the traditional cost structures of
the ailines,'' labor, supplies and debt financing, said James Carey,
research vice president for Airline Economics Inc. in Washington.
   In 1985, Lorenzo made unsuccessful passes at TWA and Frontier
Airlines.
   A year later, with Continental still in bankruptcy court, Texas
Air snatched foundering People Express, with its Newark, N.J. hub,
and the assets of People Express subsidiary Frontier, which provided
a Denver base, for about $300 million. The Eastern deal, for $676
million, followed shortly.
   Industry sources said Lorenzo bought Eastern to get the final
piece of the puzzle _ a computerized national reservation system
that he transferred to Texas Air for a bargain price of $100
million. One source said Eastern was offered $350 million for the
computer system alone.
   His critics say Lorenzo's goal then was to get concessions from
Eastern's unions and pare down the money-losing carrier even more;
Eastern sold its Kansas City, Mo., hub last year, and with court
approval plans to sell the Northeast shuttle to Donald Trump and
gates and routes from Philadelphia.
   Bankruptcy protection allows Lorenzo the chance to reduce labor
costs even more by seeking to dissolve union contracts on the
grounds that Eastern was propelled into court by the pilots' walkout.
   ``He moves stuff around and he tries to build houses of cards,''
one critic said. ``Even when they're collapsing, as in bankruptcy,
he'll find some new and novel way to exploit it further. It's as if
the collapse was planned.''
   Lorenzo defenders say he exploited industry turmoil following
deregulation in 1978 and cannily crafted the megacarrier he sought,
if at the expense of tens of thousands of jobs, stranded passengers
and unpaid creditors.
   ``With deregulation and the ability to shift assets and merge and
acquire with relative freedom, what Frank has been doing is probably
part of a general trend in this country,'' said Carey of Airline
Economics.
   ``The big distinction you make with Lorenzo and airline
managements is he is more of a specialist on the art of the
financial side _ what Trump calls the art of the deal _ than most
managers, who have a history and background in the airline,'' he
said.
   Lorenzo would agree.
   ``The issue,'' he said last week after Eastern filed for Chapter
11, ``is fundamentally whether a troubled and sick business in a
competitive marketplace should be allowed to change itself and
manage its survival.''
   End adv for Sunday March 12
</TEXT>
